{"title_page": "Habbari dynasty", "text_new": "{{Infobox country\n| native_name                = \n| conventional_long_name                = Habbari Emirate of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]]\n| common_name                = Sindh, Balochistan, Gujarat\n| status                = \n| year_start                = 854\n| year_end                = 1011\n| date_start                = \n| date_end                = \n| event_start                = Habbari dynasty begins\n| event_end                = Habbari dynasty ends\n| p1                = Brahman dynasty\n| flag_p1                = Sindh_700ad.jpg\n| p2                = \n| flag_p2                = \n| s1                = Ghaznavid dynasty\n| flag_s1                = \n| s2                = Samma dynasty\n| flag_s2                = \n| image_flag                = \n| image_map                = \n| image_map_caption                = \n| national_anthem                = \n| capital                = [[Mansura, Sindh|Mansura]]\n| common_languages                = [[Arabic language|Arabic]]<br>[[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]\n| government_type                = [[Emirate]]\n| title_leader                = \n| leader1                = 'Umar bin Aziz al-Habbari\n| year_leader1                = \n| leader2                = \n| year_leader2                = \n| footnotes                = \n| demonym                = \n| area_km2                = \n| area_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| today                = [[Pakistan]]\n| religion                = [[Sunni Islam]]\n}}\n{{History of Pakistan}}\nThe '''Habbari''' were an [[Arabs|Arab]] dynasty that ruled much of Greater [[Sindh]], in modern-day [[Pakistan]], as a semi-independent ''emirate'' from 841 to 1024. Beginning with the rule of 'Umar bin Abdul Aziz al-Habbari in 841 CE, the region became semi-independent from the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in 854, while continuing to nominally pledge allegiance to the Abbasid Caliph in [[Baghdad]].<ref name=\"Asimov\">P. M. (M.S. Asimov, Vadim Mikha\u012dlovich Masson, Ahmad Hasan Dani, Unesco, Clifford Edmund Bosworth), ''The History of Civilizations of Central Asia'', UNESCO, 1999, {{ISBN|81-208-1595-5}}, {{ISBN|978-81-208-1595-7}} pg 293-294.</ref><ref name=\"Singh\">P. M. ( Nagendra Kumar Singh), ''Muslim Kingship in India'', Anmol Publications, 1999, {{ISBN|81-261-0436-8}}, {{ISBN|978-81-261-0436-9}} pg 43-45.</ref><ref name=\"Maclean\">P. M. ( Derryl N. Maclean), ''Religion and society in Arab Sindh'', Published by Brill, 1989, {{ISBN|90-04-08551-3}}, {{ISBN|978-90-04-08551-0}} pg 140-143.</ref> The Habbari ascension marked the end of a period of direct rule of Sindh by the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] and Abbasid Caliphates, which had begun in 711 CE.  \n\nThe Habbaris were based in the city of [[Mansura (Brahmanabad)|Mansura]], and ruled central and southern Sindh south of [[Aror]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ap8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA26&dq=arab+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP87SLz6joAhWCtJ4KHdIsD9oQ6AEwBXoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=arab%20sindh&f=false|title=A Gazetteer of the Province of Sindh|date=1874|publisher=G. Bell and Sons|language=en}}</ref> near the modern-day metropolis of [[Sukkur]]. The Habbaris ruled Sindh until they were defeated by [[Sultan]] [[Mahmud of Ghazni|Mahmud Ghaznavi]] in 1026, who then went on to destroy the old Habbari capital of Mansura, and annex the region to the [[Ghaznavid|Ghaznavid empire]], thereby ending Arab rule of Sindh.\n\n== Background ==\nThe region of Greater Sindh was first brought under Arab Islamic rule after the conquest of the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] general [[Muhammad bin Qasim|Muhammad Bin Qasim]] in 711 CE, and formed the easternmost province of the Islamic empire. The region corresponded to an area greater in area than the modern Pakistani province, and included the Makran coast, central Balochistan, and southern Punjab, which in sum correspond to much of the territory of modern Pakistan.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=MacLean|first=Derryl N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxAVAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIyJ_2tajoAhXzJzQIHcPkDpkQ6AEwB3oECAgQAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Religion and Society in Arab Sind|date=1989|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-08551-0|language=en}}</ref> The province's internal administration was largely delegated to the natives, rather than the Arab conquerers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Sindh_700ad.jpg|thumb|left|Greater Sindh]]\n\nAccording to Arab accounts of the initial conquest, central and southern Sindh was largely Buddhist - corresponding to the regions south of the old capital of [[Aror]],<ref name=\":1\" /> although these regions had a large Hindu population as well.<ref name=\":1\" /> Upper Sindh, however, had few Buddhists, and was overhelmingly Hindu.<ref name=\":1\" /> The accounts of Buddhists in Sindh was also noted by [[Xuanzang]], who visited Sindh shortly before the Arab conquest,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Naik|first=C. D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VrlLNltm5dMC&pg=PA36&dq=xuanzang+sindh+buddhist&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjfm9jlwajoAhUDvp4KHfYkAUgQ6AEwA3oECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=xuanzang%20sindh%20buddhist&f=false|title=Buddhism and Dalits: Social Philosophy and Traditions|date=2010|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-7835-792-8|language=en}}</ref> and by the Korean monk [[Hyecho]], who travelled in Sindh shortly after the Arab conquest.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jr|first=Donald S. Lopez|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SNA6DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=xuanzang+sindh+buddhist&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjfm9jlwajoAhUDvp4KHfYkAUgQ6AEwAnoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=sindh&f=false|title=Hyecho's Journey: The World of Buddhism|date=2017-12-21|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-51806-0|language=en}}</ref> \n\nUmayyad rule over Sindh was quickly supplanted by the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] of [[Baghdad]] in 750.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Asimov|first=Muchammed Sajfiddinovi\u0109|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lodSckjlNuMC&pg=PA301&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIyJ_2tajoAhXzJzQIHcPkDpkQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=habbari%20sindh&f=false|title=History of Civilizations of Central Asia|last2=Dani|first2=Ahmad Hasan|last3=Bosworth|first3=Clifford Edmund|date=1992|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-1595-7|language=en}}</ref> The new Abbasid governor of Sindh, Hisham bin 'Amr al-Taghlibi further consolidated Abbasid power in the region. In the early 9th century, Abbasid authority began to weaken. Sindh's governor, Bashar bin Daud, led a short-lived revolt against the Abbasid caliph, but quickly surrendered in exchange for a pardon.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ap8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA26&dq=arab+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP87SLz6joAhWCtJ4KHdIsD9oQ6AEwBXoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=arab%20sindh&f=false|title=A Gazetteer of the Province of Sindh|date=1874|publisher=G. Bell and Sons|language=en}}</ref> Abbasid rule continued to weaken, however, leading to the establishment of five semi-independent Arab principalities in Greater Sindh, based in [[Mansura, Sindh|Mansura]], [[Multan]], Qusdar (modern [[Khuzdar]]), and [[Mashkai|Mashkey]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== The Habbari Emirate ==\nThe Habbari were a [[Quraysh]] tribe<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=MacLean|first=Derryl N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxAVAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi52caTyqjoAhV9FTQIHQq4ATcQ6AEwBnoECAcQAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Religion and Society in Arab Sind|date=1989|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-08551-0|language=en}}</ref> that had played an active role in the politics of [[Nejd]] in the [[Arabian Peninsula]] since Pre-Islamic times, and gained prominence during Umayyad rule. The ancestors of 'Umar bin Abdul Aziz, the founder of the Habbari emirate, came to Greater Sindh as Arab settlers almost five or six generations prior to the establishment of Habbari rule in Sindh. The Habbari family acquired an agricultural estate in the village of ''Baniya'', where they engaged in agriculture and in commerce, later achieving prominence among Sindh's Arab settlers. \n\nArab tribes became rebellious in Sindh in the early 9th century during the Umayyad period. During a period of strife in 841-2 between Yemeni and Hijazi tribes, 'Umar bin Abdul Aziz al-Habbari's Hijazi faction assassinated the pro-Yemeni Abbasid governor of Sindh, Imran bin Musa [[Barmakids|Barmaki]],<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nadvi|first=Syed Sulaiman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WcMgAAAAMAAJ&q=imran+habarri&dq=imran+habarri&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwja-p_N2KjoAhUKvp4KHeCKCOoQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg|title=Indo-Arab Relations: An English Rendering of Arab O\u02be Hind Ke Ta\u02bellugat|date=1962|publisher=Institute of Indo-Middle East Cultural Studies|language=en}}</ref> leaving the Umar bin Abdul Aziz al-Habbari as the ''de facto'' governor of Sindh. According to [[Ya'qubi|al-Ya'qubi]], Umar's request to be formally appointed governor was granted in 854 by the Abbasid caliph [[Al-Mutawakkil]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Boivin|first=Michel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bXYMAQAAMAAJ&q=habbari+sindh&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipwLeXxajoAhVSop4KHWAPAqs4ChDoATABegQIARAC|title=Sindh Through History and Representations: French Contributions to Sindhi Studies|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-547503-6|language=en}}</ref> Following the death of Al-Mutawakkil in 861, 'Umar bin Aziz al-Habbari then established himself as an independent ruler, although he continued to read the Friday prayers in the name of the Abbasid caliph,<ref name=\":2\" /> thereby nominally pledging allegiance to the Abbasid Caliph in Baghdad. \n\nThe state established by the Habbaris came to be known as ''Mansura,<ref name=\":2\" />'' named after the city which was designated their capital in 883.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=Finbarr Barry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q0_YAAAAMAAJ&q=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&dq=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi52caTyqjoAhV9FTQIHQq4ATcQ6AEwAXoECAMQAg|title=Piety and Politics in the Early Indian Mosque|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-569512-0|language=en}}</ref> The Mansura state ruled by the Umar bin Abdul Aziz Habbari controlled the region between the [[Arabian Sea]] and [[Aror]],<ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Khuzdar]] in central Balochistan. The region around the city of [[Aror]] continued to be ruled by its local Hindu Raja, who acted as a subordinate of the Habbari emirate.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Khan|first=Ahmad Nabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0HlCAAAAYAAJ&q=habbari+sindh&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipwLeXxajoAhVSop4KHWAPAqs4ChDoATACegQIABAC|title=Al-Mansurah: A Forgotten Arab Metropolis in Pakistan|date=1990|publisher=Department of Archaeology & Museums, Government of Pakistan|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOther parts of Greater Sindh did not fall under Habbari rule after the collapse of direct Abbasid rule. The ''Banu Munabih'' established an emirate in [[Multan]],<ref name=\":2\" /> the Banu Ma'dan established an emirate in [[Makran]] before annexing the short-lived emirate of Mashkey. The Habbari ruled over the area of ''Turan'' (modern [[Khuzdar]]), until the end of the 9th century, when its chief Mughira bin Ahmad established his independence and moved his capital to ''Kijkanan'' (modern [[Kalat, Pakistan|Kalat]]).<ref name=\":2\" /> After the secession of Greater Sindh from the Caliphate, there was no basic change in the character of the regime and the newly established Habbari state continued to function on the lines set by the Umayyads and the Abbasids. \n\n'Umar bin Aziz al-Habbari ruled until around 884, when his son Abdullah bin Umar took power until around 914. He, in turn, was followed by  'Umar bin Abdullah until around 943. During the rule of the first 3 Habbari rulers, caravan routes from Persia were routed into the Habbari capital of Mansura, before continuing westward into the rest of the Indian Subcontinent.<ref name=\":2\" /> The routing of trade through Mansura made it a wealthy city, as confirmed by the accounts of [[Istakhri]], [[Ibn Hawqal]], and [[Al-Maqdisi]] who had all visited the city.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n5 more members of the Habbari family held the office of ''Emir'' of Mansura until 1025 C.E. The state was then under the rule of [[Tahirids]], [[Saffarids]], [[Samanids]], until being conquered by [[Ghaznavids]] in 1026. Mahmud Ghaznavi regarded the Abbasids to be the true Caliphs, and regarded the Habbaris as representative of ongoing Umayyad rule, despite their nominal allegiance to the Abbasid caliph, since they had originally migrated and gained prominence in Sindh under Umayyad rule.\n\n== Religious beliefs ==\nThe first Habbaris were followers of the Sunni school of thought, and pledged allegiance to the Sunni caliphs in Baghdad, although the last Habbari ruler, [[Khafif]], may have converted to [[Isma'ilism|Isma'ili]] Islam.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Virani|first=Shafique N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXt2CAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjt7NfAy6joAhWVt54KHUm3BnA4FBDoATABegQIBhAC#v=onepage&q=Sindh&f=false|title=The Ismailis in the Middle Ages: A History of Survival, a Search for Salvation|date=2007-04-19|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-029520-2|language=en}}</ref> Under Habarri rule, Ismaili missionaries, who pledged allegiance to the [[Fatimid Caliphate]] in [[Cairo]], became active in Sindh, which became one of 12 ''jaza'ir,'' or \"islands\" in the Islamic world in which Ismaili missionary activity was successful.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 957, al-Qadi al-Nu'man recorded that an Ismaili ''da'i'' travelled throughout Sindh in the mid-10th century, and successfully converted large numbers of non-Muslims to Ismaili Islam.<ref name=\":4\" /> By 985, [[Al-Maqdisi]] noted that the population of [[Multan]] (in northern Greater [[Sindh]], ruled by the Banu Munnabih) was largely Shia,<ref name=\":4\" /> although the population of [[Mansura, Sindh|Mansura]] pledged allegiance to the Sunni Imam [[Dawud al-Zahiri|Daud Zahiri ibn Athir]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sastri|first=Kallidaikurichi Aiyah Nilakanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UEwwAQAAIAAJ&q=habbari+sunni+imam&dq=habbari+sunni+imam&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjjvbbIzqjoAhWJt54KHRbhAeUQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg|title=A Comprehensive History of India|last2=Congress|first2=Indian History|date=190?|publisher=Orient Longmans|isbn=978-81-7304-561-5|language=en}}</ref> Following the conquest of Multan by Mahmud Ghaznavi in 1005, who is noted to have massacred the Ismaili population, large numbers of Ismailis fled south to Mansura, where Ismailism continued even after the Ghaznavid invasion,<ref name=\":4\" /> and became the religion of the [[Soomra dynasty]] that would rule Sindh in later centuries.\n\nCentral and southern Sindh was largely Buddhist south of [[Aror]],<ref name=\":1\" /> but during the Arab rule of Sindh, Buddhism was largely extinguished, while Hinduism continued on.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==List of Habbari Emirs ==\n\n''Note: the dates below are only approximate.<ref>http://prr.hec.gov.pk/Chapters/3761H-1.pdf</ref>''\n\n* Umar ibn'Abd al-Aziz al'Habbari (855-884)\n* Abdullah bin Umar (884-913)\n* Umar bin-Abdullah (913-943)\n* Muhammad bin Abdullah (943-973)\n* Ali bin Umar (973-987)\n* Isa bin ali\n* Manbi ibn Ali bin Umar (987-1010)\n* [[Khafif]] (Soomra dynasty) (1010-1025)\n\n==See also ==\n*[[Soomra dynasty]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091026231257/http://geocities.com/ancientcoinsofindia/Amirsofsind.htm Coins of Habbarids Dynasty]\n\n{{History of Sindh}}\n\n[[Category:History of Sindh| ]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Vassal rulers of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Muslim dynasties]]\n[[Category:854 establishments]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox country\n| native_name                = \n| conventional_long_name                = Habbari Emirate of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]]\n| common_name                = Sindh, Balochistan, Gujarat\n| status                = \n| year_start                = 854\n| year_end                = 1011\n| date_start                = \n| date_end                = \n| event_start                = Habbari dynasty begins\n| event_end                = Habbari dynasty ends\n| p1                = Brahman dynasty\n| flag_p1                = Sindh_700ad.jpg\n| p2                = \n| flag_p2                = \n| s1                = Ghaznavid dynasty\n| flag_s1                = \n| s2                = Samma dynasty\n| flag_s2                = \n| image_flag                = \n| image_map                = \n| image_map_caption                = \n| national_anthem                = \n| capital                = [[Mansura, Sindh|Mansura]]\n| common_languages                = [[Arabic language|Arabic]]<br>[[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]\n| government_type                = [[Emirate]]\n| title_leader                = \n| leader1                = 'Umar bin Aziz al-Habbari\n| year_leader1                = \n| leader2                = \n| year_leader2                = \n| footnotes                = \n| demonym                = \n| area_km2                = \n| area_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| today                = [[Pakistan]]\n| religion                = [[Sunni Islam]]\n}}\n{{History of Pakistan}}\nThe '''Habbari''' were an [[Arabs|Arab]] dynasty that ruled much of Greater [[Sindh]], in modern-day [[Pakistan]], as a semi-independent ''emirate'' from 841 to 1024. Beginning with the rule of 'Umar bin Abdul Aziz al-Habbari in 841 CE, the region became semi-independent from the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] in 854, while continuing to nominally pledge allegiance to the Abbasid Caliph in [[Baghdad]].<ref name=\"Asimov\">P. M. (M.S. Asimov, Vadim Mikha\u012dlovich Masson, Ahmad Hasan Dani, Unesco, Clifford Edmund Bosworth), ''The History of Civilizations of Central Asia'', UNESCO, 1999, {{ISBN|81-208-1595-5}}, {{ISBN|978-81-208-1595-7}} pg 293-294.</ref><ref name=\"Singh\">P. M. ( Nagendra Kumar Singh), ''Muslim Kingship in India'', Anmol Publications, 1999, {{ISBN|81-261-0436-8}}, {{ISBN|978-81-261-0436-9}} pg 43-45.</ref><ref name=\"Maclean\">P. M. ( Derryl N. Maclean), ''Religion and society in Arab Sindh'', Published by Brill, 1989, {{ISBN|90-04-08551-3}}, {{ISBN|978-90-04-08551-0}} pg 140-143.</ref> The Habbari ascension marked the end of a period of direct rule of Sindh by the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] and Abbasid Caliphates, which had begun in 711 CE.  \n\nThe Habbaris were based in the city of [[Mansura (Brahmanabad)|Mansura]], and ruled central and southern Sindh south of [[Aror]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ap8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA26&dq=arab+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP87SLz6joAhWCtJ4KHdIsD9oQ6AEwBXoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=arab%20sindh&f=false|title=A Gazetteer of the Province of Sindh|date=1874|publisher=G. Bell and Sons|language=en}}</ref> near the modern-day metropolis of [[Sukkur]]. The Habbaris ruled Sindh until they were defeated by [[Sultan]] [[Mahmud of Ghazni|Mahmud Ghaznavi]] in 1026, who then went on to destroy the old Habbari capital of Mansura, and annex the region to the [[Ghaznavid|Ghaznavid empire]], thereby ending Arab rule of Sindh.\n\n== Background ==\nThe region of Greater Sindh was first brought under Arab Islamic rule after the conquest of the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] general [[Muhammad bin Qasim|Muhammad Bin Qasim]] in 711 CE, and formed the easternmost province of the Islamic empire. The region corresponded to an area greater in area than the modern Pakistani province, and included the Makran coast, central Balochistan, and southern Punjab, which in sum correspond to much of the territory of modern Pakistan.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=MacLean|first=Derryl N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxAVAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIyJ_2tajoAhXzJzQIHcPkDpkQ6AEwB3oECAgQAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Religion and Society in Arab Sind|date=1989|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-08551-0|language=en}}</ref> The province's internal administration was largely delegated to the natives, rather than the Arab conquerers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Sindh_700ad.jpg|thumb|left|Greater Sindh]]\n\nAccording to Arab accounts of the initial conquest, central and southern Sindh was largely Buddhist - corresponding to the regions south of the old capital of [[Aror]],<ref name=\":1\" /> although these regions had a large Hindu population as well.<ref name=\":1\" /> Upper Sindh, however, had few Buddhists, and was overhelmingly Hindu.<ref name=\":1\" /> The accounts of Buddhists in Sindh was also noted by [[Xuanzang]], who visited Sindh shortly before the Arab conquest,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Naik|first=C. D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VrlLNltm5dMC&pg=PA36&dq=xuanzang+sindh+buddhist&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjfm9jlwajoAhUDvp4KHfYkAUgQ6AEwA3oECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=xuanzang%20sindh%20buddhist&f=false|title=Buddhism and Dalits: Social Philosophy and Traditions|date=2010|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-7835-792-8|language=en}}</ref> and by the Korean monk [[Hyecho]], who travelled in Sindh shortly after the Arab conquest.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jr|first=Donald S. Lopez|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SNA6DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=xuanzang+sindh+buddhist&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjfm9jlwajoAhUDvp4KHfYkAUgQ6AEwAnoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=sindh&f=false|title=Hyecho's Journey: The World of Buddhism|date=2017-12-21|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-51806-0|language=en}}</ref> \n\nUmayyad rule over Sindh was quickly supplanted by [[Abbasid Caliphate]] of [[Baghdad]] in 750.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Asimov|first=Muchammed Sajfiddinovi\u0109|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lodSckjlNuMC&pg=PA301&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIyJ_2tajoAhXzJzQIHcPkDpkQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=habbari%20sindh&f=false|title=History of Civilizations of Central Asia|last2=Dani|first2=Ahmad Hasan|last3=Bosworth|first3=Clifford Edmund|date=1992|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-1595-7|language=en}}</ref> The new Abbasid governor of Sindh, Hisham bin 'Amr al-Taghlibi further consolidated Abbasid power in the region. In the early 9th century, Abbasid authority began to weaken. Sindh's governor Bashar bin Daud lead a short-lived revolt against the Abbasid caliph, but quickly surrendered in exchange for pardon.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ap8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA26&dq=arab+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP87SLz6joAhWCtJ4KHdIsD9oQ6AEwBXoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=arab%20sindh&f=false|title=A Gazetteer of the Province of Sindh|date=1874|publisher=G. Bell and Sons|language=en}}</ref> Abbasid rule continued to weaken, however, leading to the establishment of 5 semi-independent Arab principalities in Greater Sindh, based in [[Mansura, Sindh|Mansura]], [[Multan]], Qusdar (modern [[Khuzdar]]), and [[Mashkai|Mashkey]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== The Habbari Emirate ==\nThe Habbari were a [[Quraysh]] tribe<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=MacLean|first=Derryl N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xxAVAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi52caTyqjoAhV9FTQIHQq4ATcQ6AEwBnoECAcQAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Religion and Society in Arab Sind|date=1989|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-08551-0|language=en}}</ref> that had played an active role in the politics of [[Nejd]] in the [[Arabian Peninsula]] since Pre-Islamic times, and gained prominence during Umayyad rule. The ancestors of 'Umar bin Abdul Aziz, the founder of the Habbari emirate, came to Greater Sindh as Arab settlers almost five or six generations prior to the establishment of Habbari rule in Sindh. The Habbari family acquired an agricultural estate in the village of ''Baniya'', where they engaged in agriculture and in commerce, later achieving prominence among Sindh's Arab settlers. \n\nArab tribes became rebellious in Sindh in the early 9th century during the Umayyad period. During a period of strife in 841-2 between Yemeni and Hijazi tribes, 'Umar bin Abdul Aziz al-Habbari's Hijazi faction assassinated the pro-Yemeni Abbasid governor of Sindh, Imran bin Musa [[Barmakids|Barmaki]],<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nadvi|first=Syed Sulaiman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WcMgAAAAMAAJ&q=imran+habarri&dq=imran+habarri&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwja-p_N2KjoAhUKvp4KHeCKCOoQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg|title=Indo-Arab Relations: An English Rendering of Arab O\u02be Hind Ke Ta\u02bellugat|date=1962|publisher=Institute of Indo-Middle East Cultural Studies|language=en}}</ref> leaving the Umar bin Abdul Aziz al-Habbari as the ''de facto'' governor of Sindh. According to [[Ya'qubi|al-Ya'qubi]], Umar's request to be formally appointed governor was granted in 854 by the Abbasid caliph [[Al-Mutawakkil]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Boivin|first=Michel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bXYMAQAAMAAJ&q=habbari+sindh&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipwLeXxajoAhVSop4KHWAPAqs4ChDoATABegQIARAC|title=Sindh Through History and Representations: French Contributions to Sindhi Studies|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-547503-6|language=en}}</ref> Following the death of Al-Mutawakkil in 861, 'Umar bin Aziz al-Habbari then established himself as an independent ruler, although he continued to read the Friday prayers in the name of the Abbasid caliph,<ref name=\":2\" /> thereby nominally pledging allegiance to the Abbasid Caliph in Baghdad. \n\nThe state established by the Habbaris came to be known as ''Mansura,<ref name=\":2\" />'' named after the city which was designated their capital in 883.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=Finbarr Barry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q0_YAAAAMAAJ&q=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&dq=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi52caTyqjoAhV9FTQIHQq4ATcQ6AEwAXoECAMQAg|title=Piety and Politics in the Early Indian Mosque|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-569512-0|language=en}}</ref> The Mansura state ruled by the Umar bin Abdul Aziz Habbari controlled the region between the [[Arabian Sea]] and [[Aror]],<ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Khuzdar]] in central Balochistan. The region around the city of [[Aror]] continued to be ruled by its local Hindu Raja, who acted as a subordinate of the Habbari emirate.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Khan|first=Ahmad Nabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0HlCAAAAYAAJ&q=habbari+sindh&dq=habbari+sindh&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwipwLeXxajoAhVSop4KHWAPAqs4ChDoATACegQIABAC|title=Al-Mansurah: A Forgotten Arab Metropolis in Pakistan|date=1990|publisher=Department of Archaeology & Museums, Government of Pakistan|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOther parts of Greater Sindh did not fall under Habbari rule after the collapse of direct Abbasid rule. The ''Banu Munabih'' established an emirate in [[Multan]],<ref name=\":2\" /> the Banu Ma'dan established an emirate in [[Makran]] before annexing the short-lived emirate of Mashkey. The Habbari ruled over the area of ''Turan'' (modern [[Khuzdar]]), until the end of the 9th century, when its chief Mughira bin Ahmad established his independence and moved his capital to ''Kijkanan'' (modern [[Kalat, Pakistan|Kalat]]).<ref name=\":2\" /> After the secession of Greater Sindh from the Caliphate, there was no basic change in the character of the regime and the newly established Habbari state continued to function on the lines set by the Umayyads and the Abbasids. \n\n'Umar bin Aziz al-Habbari ruled until around 884, when his son Abdullah bin Umar took power until around 914. He, in turn, was followed by  'Umar bin Abdullah until around 943. During the rule of the first 3 Habbari rulers, caravan routes from Persia were routed into the Habbari capital of Mansura, before continuing westward into the rest of the Indian Subcontinent.<ref name=\":2\" /> The routing of trade through Mansura made it a wealthy city, as confirmed by the accounts of [[Istakhri]], [[Ibn Hawqal]], and [[Al-Maqdisi]] who had all visited the city.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n5 more members of the Habbari family held the office of ''Emir'' of Mansura until 1025 C.E. The state was then under the rule of [[Tahirids]], [[Saffarids]], [[Samanids]], until being conquered by [[Ghaznavids]] in 1026. Mahmud Ghaznavi regarded the Abbasids to be the true Caliphs, and regarded the Habbaris as representative of ongoing Umayyad rule, despite their nominal allegiance to the Abbasid caliph, since they had originally migrated and gained prominence in Sindh under Umayyad rule.\n\n== Religious beliefs ==\nThe first Habbaris were followers of the Sunni school of thought, and pledged allegiance to the Sunni caliphs in Baghdad, although the last Habbari ruler, [[Khafif]], may have converted to [[Isma'ilism|Isma'ili]] Islam.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Virani|first=Shafique N.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXt2CAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mahmud+ghaznavi+habbari+umayyad&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjt7NfAy6joAhWVt54KHUm3BnA4FBDoATABegQIBhAC#v=onepage&q=Sindh&f=false|title=The Ismailis in the Middle Ages: A History of Survival, a Search for Salvation|date=2007-04-19|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-029520-2|language=en}}</ref> Under Habarri rule, Ismaili missionaries, who pledged allegiance to the [[Fatimid Caliphate]] in [[Cairo]], became active in Sindh, which became one of 12 ''jaza'ir,'' or \"islands\" in the Islamic world in which Ismaili missionary activity was successful.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 957, al-Qadi al-Nu'man recorded that an Ismaili ''da'i'' travelled throughout Sindh in the mid-10th century, and successfully converted large numbers of non-Muslims to Ismaili Islam.<ref name=\":4\" /> By 985, [[Al-Maqdisi]] noted that the population of [[Multan]] (in northern Greater [[Sindh]], ruled by the Banu Munnabih) was largely Shia,<ref name=\":4\" /> although the population of [[Mansura, Sindh|Mansura]] pledged allegiance to the Sunni Imam [[Dawud al-Zahiri|Daud Zahiri ibn Athir]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sastri|first=Kallidaikurichi Aiyah Nilakanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UEwwAQAAIAAJ&q=habbari+sunni+imam&dq=habbari+sunni+imam&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjjvbbIzqjoAhWJt54KHRbhAeUQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg|title=A Comprehensive History of India|last2=Congress|first2=Indian History|date=190?|publisher=Orient Longmans|isbn=978-81-7304-561-5|language=en}}</ref> Following the conquest of Multan by Mahmud Ghaznavi in 1005, who is noted to have massacred the Ismaili population, large numbers of Ismailis fled south to Mansura, where Ismailism continued even after the Ghaznavid invasion,<ref name=\":4\" /> and became the religion of the [[Soomra dynasty]] that would rule Sindh in later centuries.\n\nCentral and southern Sindh was largely Buddhist south of [[Aror]],<ref name=\":1\" /> but during the Arab rule of Sindh, Buddhism was largely extinguished, while Hinduism continued on.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==List of Habbari Emirs ==\n\n''Note: the dates below are only approximate.<ref>http://prr.hec.gov.pk/Chapters/3761H-1.pdf</ref>''\n\n* Umar ibn'Abd al-Aziz al'Habbari (855-884)\n* Abdullah bin Umar (884-913)\n* Umar bin-Abdullah (913-943)\n* Muhammad bin Abdullah (943-973)\n* Ali bin Umar (973-987)\n* Isa bin ali\n* Manbi ibn Ali bin Umar (987-1010)\n* [[Khafif]] (Soomra dynasty) (1010-1025)\n\n==See also ==\n*[[Soomra dynasty]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091026231257/http://geocities.com/ancientcoinsofindia/Amirsofsind.htm Coins of Habbarids Dynasty]\n\n{{History of Sindh}}\n\n[[Category:History of Sindh| ]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Vassal rulers of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Muslim dynasties]]\n[[Category:854 establishments]]\n", "name_user": "HavelockWilltravel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habbari_dynasty"}
{"title_page": "Green Party (Norway)", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Green Party\n| colorcode = {{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}\n| spokesperson = [[Une Aina Bastholm]]<br />[[Arild Hermstad]]\n| foundation = 29 October 1988\n| ideology = [[Green politics]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/norway.html|title=Norway|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|date=2017|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Oslo]]\n| international = [[Global Greens]]\n| website = [http://www.mdg.no/ www.mdg.no]\n| country = Norway\n| native_name = Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne\n| logo = Milj\u00f8partiet de Gr\u00f8nne logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| european = [[European Green Party]]\n| youth_wing = [[Young Greens of Norway]]\n| position = [[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]]<ref name=\"uio\">{{cite news|author=Jupsk\u00e5s, Anders Ravik |url=http://www.sv.uio.no/isv/forskning/aktuelt/blogg/ta-politika/2011/de-gronne.html |title=En mild gr\u00f8nn vind i norske byer: MDGs lokale gjennombrudd |language=Norwegian |publisher=UiO: Institutt for statsvitenskap (ISV): Det samfunnsvitenskapelige fakultet |date=14 September 2011|quote=\"I mine unders\u00f8kelser av partienes landsm\u00f8tedelegater (de som vedtar partiets politikk) kommer det frem at partiet i all hovedsak plasserer seg p\u00e5 \u00abvenstresiden\u00bb i norsk politikk.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"vox\">{{cite news|author=Arnesen, Sveinung|title=Ligger Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne i sentrum eller til venstre?|url=http://voxpublica.no/2015/03/ligger-miljopartiet-de-gronne-i-sentrum-eller-til-venstre/|work=Vox Publica|date=9 March 2015|language=Norwegian|quote=\"Data fra Norsk medborgerpanel viser at velgerne plasserer partiet til venstre for sentrum.\"}}</ref>\n| colours = Green\n| membership_year = 2019\n| membership = {{Increase}} 9,963<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/doblet-medlemstallene-pa-to-ar/72001690 | editor=[[Dagbladet]] | title= Doblet medlemstallene p\u00e5 to \u00e5r| date= 7 January 2020 | accessdate= 20 February 2020 | lang=no-NB}}</ref>\n| seats1_title = [[Storting]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|169|hex={{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[County council (Norway)|County Councils]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|36|574|hex={{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Municipal council (Norway)|Municipal Councils]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|310|9344|hex={{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}}}\n}}\n{{Green politics sidebar}}\nThe '''Green Party''' ({{lang-nb|Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne}}, {{lang-nn|Milj\u00f8partiet Dei Gr\u00f8ne}}, literally \"Environment Party The Greens\") is a [[green politics|green]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/> [[List of political parties in Norway|political party]] in [[Norway]]. The party holds one seat in the [[Storting|Parliament of Norway]] (gaining 2.8% in the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 elections]]) and also has representation in [[Municipalities of Norway|municipal]] councils and [[County council (Norway)|county councils]] (gaining 4.2% in the [[2015 Norwegian local elections|2015 elections]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/krd/html/valg2011/bf5.html |title=Landsoversikt per parti |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924171401/http://www.regjeringen.no/krd/html/valg2011/bf5.html |archivedate=2011-09-24 }}</ref> The Green Party advocates [[green politics]], and has been described as centre-left by academics and voters.<ref name=\"uio\"/><ref name=\"vox\"/> The party itself claims distance to the two dominant right-wing and left-wing political blocs, jointly denominated as \"the fossil block\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Av Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |url=http://www.mdg.no/nyheter/verken-rod-eller-bla-men-gronn-2/ |title=Verken r\u00f8d eller bl\u00e5, men gr\u00f8nn |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |date=21 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016131307/http://www.mdg.no/nyheter/verken-rod-eller-bla-men-gronn-2/ |archive-date=16 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Green Party is a member of the [[European Green Party]] and the [[Global Greens]], and was founded with the [[Alliance '90/The Greens|German Greens]] as its stated model.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogg.bt.no/preik/2013/01/16/de-gronne-banker-pa-2/#.VDr5Mrtvt2Y|title=De Gr\u00f8nne banker p\u00e5  -  Preik|work=bt.no|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> It maintains close ties to other Green parties including the German Greens and the [[Green Party (Sweden)|Swedish Greens]].\n\n==History==\nThe process of forming a new national green party in Norway was initiated in December 1984, with the official launch in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkunne.no/default.aspx?menu=272&id=7222 |title=Milj\u00f8partiet Dei Gr\u00f8ne |publisher=Allkunne |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no}}</ref> Among the pioneers were the late philosopher [[Arne N\u00e6ss]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/jan/15/obituary-arne-naess |work=The Guardian |first=Walter |last=Schwarz |title=Obituary: Arne N\u00e6ss |date=15 January 2009}}</ref> peace researcher [[Johan Galtung]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nordlyspuls.no/-/bulletin/print/190722_johan-galtung-mottok-aeresmedlemskap?ref=mst |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120712094447/http://nordlyspuls.no/-/bulletin/print/190722_johan-galtung-mottok-aeresmedlemskap?ref=mst |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-12 |title=Nordlys : Johan Galtung mottok \u00e6resmedlemskap |publisher=Nordlyspuls.no |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no }}</ref> and the philosopher [[Sigmund Kval\u00f8y Setreng]].\n\nIn the local elections between 1991 and 2009 the Green Party had 6 - 8 representatives elected each time. In the national elections the party never exceeded 0.5% support.\n\nSince 2005, the Greens have seen a significant membership rise, with the new members coming from a wide variety of other parties, including the seven established parliamentary parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/politisk/de-groennes-historie-3976426.html |title=De Gr\u00f8nnes historie - Siste nytt - innenriks, utenriks |publisher=Tv2.no |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011 Norwegian local elections|municipal elections of 2011]], the party saw its first local breakthrough, having garnered close to 22,000 votes on a national basis. Two years later, during the campaign for the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 general election]], the party saw a significant rise in support in the opinion polls. The Greens were widely expected to gain parliamentary representation to some extent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogg.tv2.no/tom-hetland/2013/08/16/blir-dei-grone-arets-sensasjon/ |title=Blir Dei Gr\u00f8ne \u00e5rets sensasjon? |author=Tom Hetland |publisher=TV 2 |date=2013-08-16 |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no}}</ref> In the election, the Greens gathered over 79,000 votes, making them the 8th biggest party in the country. This vote count translates to 2.8 percent of the vote. [[Rasmus Hansson]], the party's top candidate from [[Oslo]] was elected to parliament, becoming the first ever Green MP.<ref>MP.http://www.nettavisen.no/politikk/article3675551.ece</ref>\n\nIn the local elections of 2015 the Green Party overtook the 4% nationally for the first time in its history and got the third place in Oslo.\n\n==Ideology==\nThe Green Party is one of the global ecologist and environmentalist political parties and movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdg.no/om-oss/ |title=Om oss |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21}}</ref> As a member of the pan-European [[European Green Party]], the Norwegian Greens subscribe to social progressivism and social justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/velferd-og-arbeidsliv/ |title=Velferd og arbeidsliv |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |accessdate=2013-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131109143543/http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/velferd-og-arbeidsliv/ |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/utvikling-og-bistand/ |title=Utvikling og bistand |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109152016/http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/utvikling-og-bistand/ |archive-date=2013-11-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The main focus of the party is environmental protection and ecological sustainability. The party seeks to introduce a tax on wasteful consumption, and to reorganise the food industry. The Greens have also pledged support for a reform in the agrarian industry, increasing the production of organic crops and strengthening the eco-friendly agricultural sector.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/tema-3-2/ |title=Livskvalitet &#124; Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |publisher=Mdg.no |accessdate=2013-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109151801/http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/tema-3-2/ |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref>\n\nThe Green party seeks to reduce the Norwegian petroleum extraction in order to counteract serious [[climate change]]. The proposal is to stop extraction by 2033.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/fornybar-fremtid/ |title=Fornybar fremtid |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517222736/https://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/fornybar-fremtid/ |archive-date=2015-05-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe party does not have a leader in the traditional sense, rather it is led by the national executive committee which consists of seven persons. Among the board members, two persons (currently [[Arild Hermstad]] and [[Une Aina Bastholm]]), act as national spokespersons for the party. All party representatives are elected during the annual party convention.\n\n==Election results==\n[[File:MDG Valgvake 2013 (10024177254).jpg|thumb|The party's member of [[Parliament of Norway|Parliament]], [[Rasmus Hansson]], being interviewed by the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] on the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 election night]]]]\n[[File:MDG Valgvake 2013 (10024221645).jpg|thumb|Former national spokeswoman [[Hanna Marcussen]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ [[Storting]] elections\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Date\n! colspan=\"3\"| Votes\n! colspan=\"2\"| Seats\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Position\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Size\n|-\n! #\n! %\n! \u00b1\n! \u00b1\n|-\n! [[1989 Norwegian parliamentary election|1989]]\n| 10,136\n| 0.4%\n| + 0.4\n| {{Composition bar|0|165|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| N/A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 9th\n|-\n! [[1993 Norwegian parliamentary election|1993]]\n| 3,054\n| 0.1%\n| - 0.3\n| {{Composition bar|0|165|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| N/A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12th\n|-\n! [[1997 Norwegian parliamentary election|1997]]\n| 5,884\n| 0.2%\n| + 0.1\n| {{Composition bar|0|165|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| N/A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 11th\n|-\n! [[2001 Norwegian parliamentary election|2001]]\n| 3,785\n| 0.2%\n| + 0.0\n| {{Composition bar|0|165|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| N/A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 13th\n|-\n! [[2005 Norwegian parliamentary election|2005]]\n| 3,652\n| 0.1%\n| - 0.1\n| {{Composition bar|0|169|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| N/A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12th\n|-\n! [[2009 Norwegian parliamentary election|2009]]\n| 9,286\n| 0.3%\n| + 0.2\n| {{Composition bar|0|169|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| N/A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 10th\n|-\n! [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013]]\n| 79,152\n| 2.8%\n| + 2.5\n| {{Composition bar|1|169|#67962e}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| style=\"background:#fcc;\"| Opposition\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8th\n|-\n! [[2017 Norwegian parliamentary election|2017]]\n| 94,427\n| 3.2%\n| + 0.4\n| {{Composition bar|1|169|#67962e}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| style=\"background:#fcc;\"| Opposition\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8th\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Green party]]\n* [[Green politics]]\n* [[List of environmental organizations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne}}\n*{{in lang|no}} [http://www.mdg.no/ Official site]\n\n{{Norwegian political parties}}\n{{Green parties}}\n\n[[Category:Green parties in Europe]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:European Green Party]]\n[[Category:Environmental organisations based in Norway]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Global Greens member parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Norway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Green Party\n| colorcode = {{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}\n| spokesperson = [[Une Aina Bastholm]]<br />[[Arild Hermstad]]\n| foundation = 29 October 1988\n| ideology = [[Green politics]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/norway.html|title=Norway|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|date=2017|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Oslo]]\n| international = [[Global Greens]]\n| website = [http://www.mdg.no/ www.mdg.no]\n| country = Norway\n| native_name = Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne\n| logo = Milj\u00f8partiet de Gr\u00f8nne logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| european = [[European Green Party]]\n| youth_wing = [[Young Greens of Norway]]\n| position = [[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]]<ref name=\"uio\">{{cite news|author=Jupsk\u00e5s, Anders Ravik |url=http://www.sv.uio.no/isv/forskning/aktuelt/blogg/ta-politika/2011/de-gronne.html |title=En mild gr\u00f8nn vind i norske byer: MDGs lokale gjennombrudd |language=Norwegian |publisher=UiO: Institutt for statsvitenskap (ISV): Det samfunnsvitenskapelige fakultet |date=14 September 2011|quote=\"I mine unders\u00f8kelser av partienes landsm\u00f8tedelegater (de som vedtar partiets politikk) kommer det frem at partiet i all hovedsak plasserer seg p\u00e5 \u00abvenstresiden\u00bb i norsk politikk.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"vox\">{{cite news|author=Arnesen, Sveinung|title=Ligger Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne i sentrum eller til venstre?|url=http://voxpublica.no/2015/03/ligger-miljopartiet-de-gronne-i-sentrum-eller-til-venstre/|work=Vox Publica|date=9 March 2015|language=Norwegian|quote=\"Data fra Norsk medborgerpanel viser at velgerne plasserer partiet til venstre for sentrum.\"}}</ref>\n| colours = Green\n| membership_year = 2019\n| membership = {{Increase}} 9,963<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/doblet-medlemstallene-pa-to-ar/72001690 | editor=[[Dagbladet]] | title= Doblet medlemstallene p\u00e5 to \u00e5r| date= 7 January 2020 | accessdate= 20 February 2020 | lang=no-NB}}</ref>\n| seats1_title = [[Storting]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|169|hex={{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[County council (Norway)|County Councils]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|36|574|hex={{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Municipal council (Norway)|Municipal Councils]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|310|9344|hex={{Green Party (Norway)/meta/color}}}}\n}}\n{{Green politics sidebar}}\nThe '''Green Party''' ({{lang-nb|Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne}}, {{lang-nn|Milj\u00f8partiet Dei Gr\u00f8ne}}, {{lang-sme|Birasbellodat Ruon\u00e1t}}, literally \"Environment Party The Greens\") is a [[green politics|green]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/> [[List of political parties in Norway|political party]] in [[Norway]]. The party holds one seat in the [[Storting|Parliament of Norway]] (gaining 2.8% in the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 elections]]) and also has representation in [[Municipalities of Norway|municipal]] councils and [[County council (Norway)|county councils]] (gaining 4.2% in the [[2015 Norwegian local elections|2015 elections]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/krd/html/valg2011/bf5.html |title=Landsoversikt per parti |language=Norwegian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924171401/http://www.regjeringen.no/krd/html/valg2011/bf5.html |archivedate=2011-09-24 }}</ref> The Green Party advocates [[green politics]], and has been described as centre-left by academics and voters.<ref name=\"uio\"/><ref name=\"vox\"/> The party itself claims distance to the two dominant right-wing and left-wing political blocs, jointly denominated as \"the fossil block\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Av Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |url=http://www.mdg.no/nyheter/verken-rod-eller-bla-men-gronn-2/ |title=Verken r\u00f8d eller bl\u00e5, men gr\u00f8nn |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |date=21 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016131307/http://www.mdg.no/nyheter/verken-rod-eller-bla-men-gronn-2/ |archive-date=16 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Green Party is a member of the [[European Green Party]] and the [[Global Greens]], and was founded with the [[Alliance '90/The Greens|German Greens]] as its stated model.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogg.bt.no/preik/2013/01/16/de-gronne-banker-pa-2/#.VDr5Mrtvt2Y|title=De Gr\u00f8nne banker p\u00e5  -  Preik|work=bt.no|accessdate=15 October 2016}}</ref> It maintains close ties to other Green parties including the German Greens and the [[Green Party (Sweden)|Swedish Greens]].\n\n==History==\nThe process of forming a new national green party in Norway was initiated in December 1984, with the official launch in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkunne.no/default.aspx?menu=272&id=7222 |title=Milj\u00f8partiet Dei Gr\u00f8ne |publisher=Allkunne |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no}}</ref> Among the pioneers were the late philosopher [[Arne N\u00e6ss]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/jan/15/obituary-arne-naess |work=The Guardian |first=Walter |last=Schwarz |title=Obituary: Arne N\u00e6ss |date=15 January 2009}}</ref> peace researcher [[Johan Galtung]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nordlyspuls.no/-/bulletin/print/190722_johan-galtung-mottok-aeresmedlemskap?ref=mst |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120712094447/http://nordlyspuls.no/-/bulletin/print/190722_johan-galtung-mottok-aeresmedlemskap?ref=mst |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-12 |title=Nordlys : Johan Galtung mottok \u00e6resmedlemskap |publisher=Nordlyspuls.no |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no }}</ref> and the philosopher [[Sigmund Kval\u00f8y Setreng]].\n\nIn the local elections between 1991 and 2009 the Green Party had 6 - 8 representatives elected each time. In the national elections the party never exceeded 0.5% support.\n\nSince 2005, the Greens have seen a significant membership rise, with the new members coming from a wide variety of other parties, including the seven established parliamentary parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/politisk/de-groennes-historie-3976426.html |title=De Gr\u00f8nnes historie - Siste nytt - innenriks, utenriks |publisher=Tv2.no |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011 Norwegian local elections|municipal elections of 2011]], the party saw its first local breakthrough, having garnered close to 22,000 votes on a national basis. Two years later, during the campaign for the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 general election]], the party saw a significant rise in support in the opinion polls. The Greens were widely expected to gain parliamentary representation to some extent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogg.tv2.no/tom-hetland/2013/08/16/blir-dei-grone-arets-sensasjon/ |title=Blir Dei Gr\u00f8ne \u00e5rets sensasjon? |author=Tom Hetland |publisher=TV 2 |date=2013-08-16 |accessdate=2013-11-21 |language=no}}</ref> In the election, the Greens gathered over 79,000 votes, making them the 8th biggest party in the country. This vote count translates to 2.8 percent of the vote. [[Rasmus Hansson]], the party's top candidate from [[Oslo]] was elected to parliament, becoming the first ever Green MP.<ref>MP.http://www.nettavisen.no/politikk/article3675551.ece</ref>\n\nIn the local elections of 2015 the Green Party overtook the 4% nationally for the first time in its history and got the third place in Oslo.\n\n==Ideology==\nThe Green Party is one of the global ecologist and environmentalist political parties and movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdg.no/om-oss/ |title=Om oss |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21}}</ref> As a member of the pan-European [[European Green Party]], the Norwegian Greens subscribe to social progressivism and social justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/velferd-og-arbeidsliv/ |title=Velferd og arbeidsliv |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |accessdate=2013-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131109143543/http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/velferd-og-arbeidsliv/ |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/utvikling-og-bistand/ |title=Utvikling og bistand |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109152016/http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/utvikling-og-bistand/ |archive-date=2013-11-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The main focus of the party is environmental protection and ecological sustainability. The party seeks to introduce a tax on wasteful consumption, and to reorganise the food industry. The Greens have also pledged support for a reform in the agrarian industry, increasing the production of organic crops and strengthening the eco-friendly agricultural sector.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/tema-3-2/ |title=Livskvalitet &#124; Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |publisher=Mdg.no |accessdate=2013-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109151801/http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/tema-3-2/ |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref>\n\nThe Green party seeks to reduce the Norwegian petroleum extraction in order to counteract serious [[climate change]]. The proposal is to stop extraction by 2033.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/fornybar-fremtid/ |title=Fornybar fremtid |publisher=Milj\u00f8partiet De Gr\u00f8nne |language=no |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517222736/https://www.mdg.no/politikk/politikk-fra-a-a/fornybar-fremtid/ |archive-date=2015-05-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe party does not have a leader in the traditional sense, rather it is led by the national executive committee which consists of seven persons. Among the board members, two persons (currently [[Arild Hermstad]] and [[Une Aina Bastholm]]), act as national spokespersons for the party. All party representatives are elected during the annual party convention.\n\n==Election results==\n[[File:MDG Valgvake 2013 (10024177254).jpg|thumb|The party's member of [[Parliament of Norway|Parliament]], [[Rasmus Hansson]], being interviewed by the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] on the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 election night]]]]\n[[File:MDG Valgvake 2013 (10024221645).jpg|thumb|Former national spokeswoman [[Hanna Marcussen]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ [[Storting]] elections\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Date\n! colspan=\"3\"| Votes\n! colspan=\"2\"| Seats\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Position\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Size\n|-\n! #\n! %\n! \u00b1\n! \u00b1\n|-\n! [[1989 Norwegian parliamentary election|1989]]\n