y:Global Greens member parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Norway]]\n", "name_user": "Debatabletruth", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed the Sami name to keep article closer to the style of Arbeiderpartiet, Fremskritspartiet, Senterpartiet, R\u00f8dt and etc naming conventions. This is an English wiki page about a Norwegian political party which has no affiliation to Sami parties.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Party_(Norway)"}
{"title_page": "Grigore Vieru", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n|name          = Grigore Vieru\n|image         =Grigore Vieru 1990.jpg\n|caption       = Vieru in 1990\n|office       = Member of the [[Moldovan Parliament]]\n|term_start   = 3 September 1990\n|term_end     = 27 February 1994\n|predecessor  =\n|successor    =\n|birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1935|02|14}}\n|birth_place= [[Perer\u00eeta]], [[Hotin County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]] (today [[Briceni district]], [[Moldova]])\n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|2009|1|18|1935|02|14}}\n|death_place= [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], Moldova\n|restingplace = [[Perer\u00eeta]]\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Raisa Vieru |1957|2009}}\n|relations     = Igor Vieru (brother)\n|children      = Teodor and [[C\u0103lin Vieru]]\n|profession    = Writer\n|party         = [[Popular Front of Moldova]]\n|otherparty    =\n|alma_mater    =\n|religion      = [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodoxy]]\n|blank1        = Parents\n|data1         = Eudochia and Pavel Vieru\n}}\n\n'''Grigore Vieru''' ({{IPA-ro|\u0261ri\u02c8\u0261ore vi\u02c8eru}}; 14 February 1935, [[Perer\u00eeta]], [[Greater Romania|inter-war]] [[Hotin County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]] \u2013 18 January 2009, [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], [[Moldova|Republic of Moldova]]) was a Moldovan poet and writer. He is mostly known for his poems and books for children. His poetry is characterized by vivid natural scenery, patriotism, as well as a venerated image of the sacred mother. Vieru wrote in the [[Romanian language]]. In 1993 he was elected a correspondent member of the Romanian Academy.<ref name=\"Acad.ro_2020-04-21\">{{Citation | url=https://acad.ro/bdar/armembriLit.php?vidT=V| title=Academia Romana (membri)| newspaper=Acad.ro| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in [[Perer\u00eeta]] village, [[Hotin County]], at the time, part of [[Romania]] (today part of [[Briceni district]], Moldova). His parents, Pavel and Eudochia Vieru (''n\u00e9e'' Didic) were engaged in farming. \n\nIn 1950, he graduated from the 7-grade school of his native village, after which he attended the middle school in [[Lipcani]], which he graduated in 1953.\n\n==Personal life==\nVieru was married to Raisa Vieru since 1959; they had two sons, Teodor and [[C\u0103lin Vieru]].\n\n==  Creative work ==\nHis first publishing debut was in 1957, a booklet of poems for children, ''\"Alarma\"'' (''\"Alarm\"''), appreciated by literary critics.The following year, Vieru graduated from the [[Ion Creang\u0103 Pedagogical State University]] in [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]] with a degree in history and philology. He was employed as an editor in the magazine called ''\"Sc\u00eenteia Leninist\u0103\"'' (''\"The Lenin\u2019s sparkle\"'') designed for children, currently it is called ''\"Noi\"'' (''\"We\"''), and the newspaper ''\"T\u00een\u0103rul leninist\"'' (''\"The Young Lenin\u2019s follower\"''), currently ''\"Florile Dalbe\"'' (''\"Glowing Flowers\"'').\n\nIn 1959, he became editor at the ''\"Nistru'\"' magazine, currently ''\"Basarabia\"'', a publication of the [[Writers' Union of Moldova]]. \n\nFrom 1960 to 1963, he served as editor in chief of the \"''Cartea Moldoveneasc\u0103''\" publishing house.\n\nIn 1967, Vieru's book \"Poetry for Readers of All Ages\" (published in 1965) was awarded the Moldavian Prize for Youth Literature. The following year, his book \"Your Name\" became part of the contemporary literature curriculum in Moldavian universities.\n\nHe wrote another children's story/picture book \"Bread and Dew\" which features Doru, a 4 or 5-year-old boy who lives in Chi\u0219in\u0103u with his parents.\n\nMany moldavian composers were inspired by the poetry of Grigore Vieru (songbook \"Poftim de intra\u021bi\", \"Cine crede\" etc.), the poet himself is the author of a lot of melodies (\"S\u0103 cre\u0219ti mare\" etc.) and since 1964 he began to collaborate with composer [[Yulia Tsibulskaya]] (\"Soare, soare\", \"Clopo\u021beii\", \"Stea-stea, logostea\", \"Ramule-neamule\", \"C\u00eent\u00eend cu iubire\" etc.).\n\nHe was a frequent guest of the \"Poetry House\" in [[Cociulia]] village, [[Cantemir District]]. The famous book for preschoolers ''\"Albinu\u021ba\"'' was also written here.\n\n1968 was turning point for the poet's destiny; this year became remarkable by the volume of lyrical ''\"Numele T\u0103u\"'' (\"Your name\"), with an introductory written by [[Ion Dru\u021b\u0103]]. The book was appreciated by literary critics as the most original poetic appearance. In the year of it publishing, it became a subject of the study at the university within the courses designated for the contemporary national literature. Three poems in the volume are entitled: ''[[Tudor Arghezi]]'', ''[[Lucian Blaga]]'', [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i|''Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i'']], and another two are dedicated to [[Nicolae Labi\u0219]] and [[Marin Sorescu]]. For the first time, in the post war period, such dedications has appeared in the Bessarabian lyrics.\n\n== Political activity ==\nSince 1971, Grigore Vieru has been a member of [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]].\n\nIn 1973, Grigore Vieru has passed the [[Prut]] within a delegation of Soviet writers. He participated in the meeting with the editors of the \"20th Century\" magazine: Dan Haulic\u0103, [[\u0218tefan Augustin Doina\u0219]], Ioanichie Olteanu, Geo \u0218erban, Tatiana Nicolescu. At his request, he has visited monasteries of [[Putna Monastery|Putna]], [[Vorone\u021b Monastery|Vorone\u021b]], [[Sucevi\u021ba Monastery|Sucevi\u021ba]], [[Dragomirna Monastery|Dragomirna]], [[V\u0103ratec Monastery|V\u0103ratec]]. He returned to Chi\u0219in\u0103u with a bag of books. Later the poet makes the following confession:{{cquote|''\"If somebody dreamed of getting to outer space, for my whole life I have dreamed of crossing the [[Prut River]]''\"}}\n\nIn 1974 and 1977, invited by the president of the [[Writers' Union of Romania|Romanian Writers' Union]], Vieru visited [[Bucharest]], [[Constan\u021ba]], [[Ia\u0219i]], and cities in [[Transylvania]].\n\nIn 1978, the \"[[Junimea]]\" publishing house printed \"The Friday Star\", Vieru's first work published in [[Romania]].\n\nIn 1989 he was elected member of [[Parliament of Moldova|Moldova's Parliament]] and campaigned for the [[Movement for unification of Romania and Moldova|unification of Romania and Moldova]]. The following year he was elected Honorary Member of the [[Romanian Academy]]. In 1992, the Romanian Academy recommended Vieru for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\nIn 1995, he became a member of the Board of the [[Romanian Radio Broadcasting Company]], and in 1996 he won several Romanian literary awards.\n\nIn 2000, Vieru was awarded the \"[[Mihai Eminescu|Eminescu]]\" Medal by the [[Government of Romania|Romanian government]].\n\n=== Involvement in the Bessarabia National Liberation Movement  ===\n[[File:Grigore Vieru, Ion Vatamanu si Serafim Saka.jpg|thumb|313x313px|right| Grigore Vieru, [[Ion Vatamanu]] and [[Serafim Saka]] in  '70.]]\nAt the end of the [[1980s|80s]], Grigore Vieru is in the first line of the National Liberation Movement in Bessarabia, his texts (including the songs laid on his lyrics) playing a big role in awakening of the national consciousness of Romanians in Bessarabia. Vieru is one of the founders of the People's Front of Moldova and is among the organizers and leaders of the Great National Assembly of August 27, 1989. He actively participates in the debates of the 13th session of the Supreme Soviet of the SSR, in which the [[Romanian language]] is voted as the official language and the transition to Latin spelling.\n\n==Death==\nOn January 16, 2009 Vieru suffered a serious traffic accident<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/Votes_Have_No_Language/1372065.html Death Of A Moldovan Poet]. rferl.org</ref> and was admitted to the Emergency Hospital in Chi\u0219in\u0103u. Grigore Vieru was in critical condition with polytrauma, closed cranio-cerebral trauma, cerebral contusion, and closed chest trauma, contusion of the heart and lungs and contusion of the abdominal organs, with minimal chances of survival.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2013-07-03\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/ESpVf| title=Imagini VIDEO cu ma\u015fina avariat\u0103 \u00een care se afla \u015fi Grigore Vieru. Po\u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 3, 2013| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> The road accident took place on the night of January 15 to 16, at 1:30 am on the R-3 route Chi\u0219in\u0103u \u2013 H\u00e2nce\u0219ti \u2013 Cimi\u0219lia \u2013 Basarabeasca.<ref name=\"Azi.md/ro/story/918_2020-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://www.azi.md/ro/story/918| title=Starea poetului Grigore Vieru ramane grava, medici de la Bucuresti sunt in drum spre Chisinau - Moldova Azi| newspaper=Azi.md/ro/story/918| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> At the driver\u2019s seat was Gheorghe Munteanu, emeritus artist of the Republic of Moldova and deputy director of the \"Joc\" folk dance troop of Chi\u0219in\u0103u, who being in an easier state.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2013-07-03\"/> At the time, he was out with friends celebrating the birthday of [[Mihai Eminescu]], a 19th-century Romanian poet. Vieru died on January 18, 2009, in the Emergency Hospital in Chi\u0219in\u0103u after two days after the accident, following a cardiac failure from which he could not be resuscitated.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-07-15\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/JLqD| title=(video) Grigore Vieru a murit. Eminescu l-a chemat la ceruri. Ziua \u00een\u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 15, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Mediafax_15:45\">{{Citation | url=https://www.mediafax.ro/cultura-media/poetul-grigore-vieru-a-decedat-video-3765578| title=Poetul Grigore Vieru a decedat (Video)| newspaper=Mediafax| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGrigore Vieru was buried on January 20, 2009 in Chi\u0219in\u0103u, at the Central Cemetery on Armeana street. The funeral were attended by tens of thousands of people, ''the divisions of Grigore Vieru'', as professor Dan Dungaciu called them in his article.<ref name=\"Limbaromana.md/index.php?go=articole&n=242_2020-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://limbaromana.md/index.php?go=articole&n=242| title=Diviziile lui Grigore Vieru - LimbaRomana| newspaper=Limbaromana.md/index.php?go=articole&n=242| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Chi\u0219in\u0103u had not known such funerals since the burial of the spouses Doina and Ion Aldea Teodorovici. The day of January 20, 2009 was declared a day of mourning in the Republic of Moldova, at 10:00 the whole republic having a moment of silence. Vieru's funeral was also broadcast live by [[Teleradio Moldova]].\n\n== Posterity ==\n[[File:Bd. G. Vieru.JPG|The plaque on Grigore Vieru Boulevard in Chi\u0219in\u0103u|thumb|237x237px|left]]\n\nSeveral schools in the Republic of Moldova, a boulevard in Chi\u0219in\u0103u and a street in Ia\u0219i are called in honour of Grigore Vieru.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-08-01\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/gcew| title=Iasul are o strada Grigore Vieru | newspaper=archive.vn| date= August 1, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> On February 11, 2010, three days before his birthday, the poet's bust was installed in the [[Alley of Classics, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Alley of Classics]].<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-09-15\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/jw3o| title=Bustul lui Grigore Vieru va fi instalat la 12 februarie pe Aleea Clas\u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= September 15, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\nA street in [[Buz\u0103u]] is called in honour of Grigore Vieru: ''Grigore Vieru Street''.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-07-24\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/Z2rN| title=Strada Grigore Vieru, \u00een Buz\u0103u| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 24, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1996 he won several Romanian literary awards, and in the same year on August 23rd, he won [[Order of the Republic (Moldova)]]. \n\nThe Romanian president [[Traian B\u0103sescu]] has posthumously awarded Grigore Vieru with the [[Order of the Star of Romania]], Grand Cross.<ref name=\"Flac\u0103ra TV_2015-01-19\">{{Citation | url=http://flacaratv.md/19-01-2009-poetului-grigore-vieru-i-a-fost-conferit-post-mortem-ordinul-national-steaua-romaniei.html| title=Poetului Grigore Vieru i-a fost conferit post-mortem Ordinul Na\u0163ional \u201eSteaua Rom\u00e2niei\u201d| newspaper=Flac\u0103ra TV| date= January 19, 2015| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Moments in Vieru's life ==\n[[File:Paul Mecet (12).jpg|Grigore Vieru, picture by Paul Mecet|300px|thumb]]\nIn the volume of lyrics  designed for children ''\"Trei iezi\"'' (''Three baby goats'') published in 1970, there was also the poem called ''\"Curcubeul\"'' (''The Rainbow''), in which Vieru, used the metaphor of the rainbow with three colours, praised the flag of all Romanians. In short period of time after the book publishing, the Soviet censorship withdrew the book from the bookstores, and the author was accused of diversion.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012/08/01\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/tO51| title=Poetul Basarabean Grigore Vieru| newspaper=archive.vn| date= August 1, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Also in 1970, has appeared ''The Abecedarul'' book developed by Vieru in collaboration with the writer Spiridon Vangheli. Even nowadays, this textbook, which was edited many times over time, still teaches the first class little Bessarabians. In 1989, Vieru and Vangheli also made the Latin alphabet version of ''The Abecedarul''.\n\nVieru wrote, among many others, the lyrics for the soundtrack of the cartoon film ''[[Maria, Mirabela]]'', and the Vieru\u2019s poem ''\"Drag\u0103 Otee\"'' (''Dear Otee'') has been sung by Iurie Sadovnic. Later, the song was taken over by [[Zdob \u0219i Zdub]].\n\nIn 1988, in the newspaper ''[[Literatura \u015fi Arta]]'' (''Literature and Art'') in Chi\u0219in\u0103u, the first Latin-written text from post-war Bessarabia has appeared. The author was Grigore Vieru.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2013-07-06\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/zlHKB| title=EDITORIAL: Poetul Grigore Vieru s-a preschimbat in iarba (Realitatea \u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 6, 2013| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1989, Vieru has got the approval of the Soviet authorities to publish the weekly ''Literatura si Arta'' in Latin writing, the editors of the newspaper mentioned that in all Soviet Moldova there were no typewriter of Latin letters, except the one from the Academy of Sciences of the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic|MSSR]] and of professor Iulius Popa from [[B\u0103l\u021bi]]. Under these conditions, Grigore Vieru and the editor-in-chief of ''Literatura \u0219i Arta'', [[Nicolae Dabija]], went to [[Bucharest]] to get the typewriter for the newspaper. The Romanian authorities were delaying the answer, and the antiquarian shop from which they could buy such a device was closed these days because of some technical issues. However, Vieru and Dabija were helped by the priest Vasile \u021aepordei, who brought to the station a bag containing the 31 metallic signs of the Latin alphabet, cut by him from his own typewriter. In Chi\u0219in\u0103u, the Latin signs are welded to a typewriter instead of the Cyrillic ones, so ''Literatura \u0219i Arta'' magazine became the first newspaper of Bessarabia to start systematically coming out in Latin spelling.\n\nIn 1994 the neo-communists of the [[Democratic Agrarian Party]], who came to power in Moldova, have gave up to the state hymn ''[[De\u0219teapt\u0103-te, rom\u00e2ne!]]'' (''Awake the romanian'') and have proposed to the poet Grigore Vieru and the composer [[Eugen Doga]] to compose the lyrics and the music for a new hymn. They both refuse. Grigore Vieru has wrote in the ''Literatura \u0219i Arta'' magazine the following: {{cquote|''\"Historical justice will blame the poets and composers who will dare to raise their hands on the National Hymn \"Desteapt\u0103-te Rom\u00e2ne!\" stooping instead of his historical need and brilliance.\"''}}<ref name=\"adev2014-06-09\">{{Citation | url=https://adevarul.ro/moldova/actualitate/20-ani-desteapta-te-romane-1_53955a820d133766a86b3947/index.html| title=20 de ani f\u0103r\u0103 \u201eDe\u015fteapt\u0103-te, rom\u00e2ne!\u201c| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= June 9, 2014| accessdate=April 21, 2020 |author = Https://facebook. Com/100003970736071}}</ref>\n\n== Operas ==\n* 1957 \u2013  ''\"Alarma\"'' (''Alarm'') (lyrics for children);\n* 1958 \u2013 ''\"Muzicu\u021be\"'' (''Musical notes'') (lyrics for children);\n* 1961 \u2013 ''\"F\u0103t-Frumos curcubeul \u0219i Bun\u0103 ziua, fulgilor!\"'' (''F\u0103t-Frumos the rainbow and Good morning, the flakes!'') by the \"Cartea Moldoveneasc\u0103\" publishing house;\n* 1963 \u2013 ''\"Mul\u021bumim pentru pace\"'' (''Thanks for peace'') (lyrics)  and ''\"F\u0103gura\u0219i\"'' (lyrics, stories and songs);\n* 1964 - The magazine ''\"Nistru\"'' published the poem ''\"Leg\u0103m\u00e2nt\"'' (''The Covenan''), dedicated to poet Mihai Eminescu;\n* 1965 \u2013 ''\"Versuri pentru cititorii de toate v\u00e2rstele\"'' (''The lyrics for readers of all ages''), with an introductory word written by Ion Dru\u021b\u0103 and for this lyrics the poet was awarded ''The Comsomol Republican Prize'' in the field of children's and youth literature (1967);\n* 1967 \u2013 ''\"Poezii de seama voastr\u0103\"'' (''Poems of your age'') (\"Lumina\" publishing house);\n* 1968 \u2013 ''\"B\u0103rba\u021bii Moldovei\"'' (''Moldova\u2019s Men''), designed to the \"nationalist\" Nicolae Testimi\u021beanu (\"Nistru\" magazine). The whole circulation was stopped, and the dedication taken away;\n* 1969 \u2013 ''\"Duminica cuvintelor\"'' (''The  Words of Sunday'') by \"Lumina\" publishing house with illustrations by Igor Vieru, a book much loved by pre-schoolers, which is present in every kindergarten;\n* 1970 - ''\"Abecedarul\"'' (\"Lumina\" publishing house) - in collaboration with Spiridon Vangheli and painter [[Igor Vieru]];\n* 1972 \u2013 ''\"Trei iezi\"'' (''Three baby goats'');\n* 1974 \u2013 ''\"Aproape\"'' (''Nearby'') (lyrics, with color illustrations by Isai C\u00e2rmu);\n* 1975 \u2013 ''\"Mama\"'' (''The Mother'') (\"Lumina\" publishing house - book for the little ones, illustrated by Igor Vieru);\n* 1976 \u2013 ''\"Un verde ne vede!\"''(''A green one sees us!'') (\"Lumina\" publishing house \u2013 for this volume of lyrics the poem is awarded the State Prize of the Republic of Moldova (1978);\n* 1989 \u2013 ''\"Metafore Albastre\"'' - ''\u0421\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0444\u043e\u0440\u0438'' (''The Blue metaphors'') - (\"Narodna cultura\" publishing house, [[Sofia]] - in the collection Globus poetic, translation into [[bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] by Ognean Stamboliev;\n* 2010 \u2013 ''\"Mi-e dor de piatr\u0103\"'' - ''\u0416\u0430\u043b \u043c\u0438 \u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u043c\u044a\u043a\u0430'' (''I miss the stone'') \u2013 publishing house Avangardprint, Bulgaria - translation into Bulgarian and preface by Ognean Stamboliev - 100 poems.\nIt is present in:\n* Streiflicht \u2013 Eine Auswahl zeitgen\u00f6ssischer rum\u00e4nischer Lyrik (81 rum\u00e4nische Autoren), - \"Lumina piezi\u0219\u0103\" (''Pie light'') the bilingual anthology consisted of 81 Romanian writers, translated by Christian W. Schenk, Dionysos Verlag 1994, ISBN 3980387119\n\n== The music on Vieru\u2019s lyrics ==\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/sarmaticus/d21ef57bbbd618 Maria Mirabela]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/martti/06fece8482cab1 Drag\u0103 Otee]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/septimosaur/d7a64a98dab371 Pentru Ea]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cBLl2zkyQlw R\u0103sai]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qD3LYd6ScNI Eminescu]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ve_wqvvoS30 La m\u0103n\u0103stirea C\u0103priana (Clopotul \u00cenvierii)]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uWZ4h5zCJ6o L\u0103sa\u021bi-ne \u00een legea noastr\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XdHQZo6Bdjs Dou\u0103 lacrimi gemene (Chi\u0219in\u0103u \u0219i Bucure\u0219ti)]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xb9dZr3DkrU O serenad\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HKkPPwkTQks Melancolie]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/pld/f278d31bd7bccb Ultima or\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RHzzs7KY-0Y Reaprinde\u021bi candela]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/Glory/ff1920945d5252 Mi-e dor de tine, mam\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gxZxkmWT-1M  Codrul e frumos cu floare]\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery perrow=\"\">\nFile:Grigore Vieru monument in Soroca park.jpg|Grigore Vieru in [[Soroca]]\nFile:Grigore Vieru din B\u0103l\u021bi.jpg|[[Alley of Classics, B\u0103l\u021bi]] \nFile:Galati biblioteca din Eurogara CFR Calatori.jpg|Eurostation of [[Gala\u021bi]] Grigore Vieru library \n</gallery>\n\n== Presence in English language anthologies ==\n\n* ''Testament \u2013 Anthology of Modern Romanian Verse / Testament - Antologie de Poezie Rom\u00e2n\u0103 Modern\u0103 \u2013 Bilingual Edition English & Romanian'' \u2013 [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and translator) with Eva Foster and Daniel Reynaud \u2013 [[Editura Minerva|Minerva]] Publishing 2012 and 2015 (second edition) - {{ISBN|978-973-21-1006-5}}\n* ''Testament - Anthology of Romanian Verse - American Edition -'' monolingual English language edition - [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and principal translator) with Eva Foster, Daniel Reynaud and Rochelle Bews - Australian-Romanian Academy for Culture - 2017 - {{ISBN|978-0-9953502-0-5}}\n* ''The Bessarabia of My Soul / Basarabia Sufletului Meu -'' a collection of poetry from the Republic of Moldova - bilingual English/Romanian - [[Daniel Ionita]] and Maria Tonu (editors), with Eva Foster, Daniel Reynaud and Rochelle Bews - MediaTon, Toronto, Canada - 2018 - {{ISBN|978-1-7751837-9-2}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Unification of Romania and Moldova]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Grigore Vieru}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://archive.today/OJ2CK Grigore Vieru \u2013 virtual monument]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070124013536/http://biserica.org/Churches/SfantaTreime/Bios/GrigoreVieru.html A biography of Grigore Vieru]\n* {{in lang|ro}} {{YouTube|gxZxkmWT-1M|The forest is beautiful with a flower (Iu.\u0162ibulschi \u2013 Gr.Vieru)}}\n* {{in lang|ro}} {{YouTube|KehpQBEiN0g|Christ is not to blame (Iu. \u0162ibulschi \u2013 Gr. Vieru)}}\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.poezie.ro/index.php/essay/1819124/Pe_cer_a_mai_urcat_o_stea Valerian Ciobanu-Vieru: Pe cer a mai urcat o stea], poezie.ro\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.formula-as.ro/2009/853/planete-culturale-30/la-moartea-lui-grigore-vieru-10684 La moartea lui Grigore Vieru]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.formula-as.ro/2011/958/planete-culturale-30/grigore-vieru-evocare-de-nicolae-dabija-13446 GRIGORE VIERU - Evocare de NICOLAE DABIJA]\n\n{{Anti-communism in Bessarabia and Northern Bukovina}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vieru, Grigore}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Briceni District]]\n[[Category:Moldovan poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian poets]]\n[[Category:Romanian male poets]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Star of Romania]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Corresponding members of the Romanian Academy]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Republic (Moldova)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n|name          = Grigore Vieru\n|image         =Grigore Vieru 1990.jpg\n|caption       = Vieru in 1990\n|office       = Member of the [[Moldovan Parliament]]\n|term_start   = 3 September 1990\n|term_end     = 27 February 1994\n|predecessor  =\n|successor    =\n|birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1935|02|14}}\n|birth_place= [[Perer\u00eeta]], [[Hotin County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]] (today [[Briceni district]], [[Moldova]])\n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|2009|1|18|1935|02|14}}\n|death_place= [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], Moldova\n|restingplace = [[Perer\u00eeta]]\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Raisa Vieru |1957|2009}}\n|relations     = Igor Vieru (brother)\n|children      = Teodor and [[C\u0103lin Vieru]]\n|profession    = Writer\n|party         = [[Popular Front of Moldova]]\n|otherparty    =\n|alma_mater    =\n|religion      = [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodoxy]]\n|blank1        = Parents\n|data1         = Eudochia and Pavel Vieru\n}}\n\n'''Grigore Vieru''' ({{IPA-ro|\u0261ri\u02c8\u0261ore vi\u02c8eru}}; 14 February 1935, [[Perer\u00eeta]], [[Greater Romania|inter-war]] [[Hotin County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]] \u2013 18 January 2009, [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], [[Moldova|Republic of Moldova]]) was a Moldovan poet and writer. He is mostly known for his poems and books for children. His poetry is characterized by vivid natural scenery, patriotism, as well as a venerated image of the sacred mother. Vieru wrote in the [[Romanian language]]. In 1993 he was elected a correspondent member of the Romanian Academy.<ref name=\"Acad.ro_2020-04-21\">{{Citation | url=https://acad.ro/bdar/armembriLit.php?vidT=V| title=Academia Romana (membri)| newspaper=Acad.ro| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in [[Perer\u00eeta]] village, [[Hotin County]], at the time, part of [[Romania]] (today part of [[Briceni district]], Moldova). His parents, Pavel and Eudochia Vieru (''n\u00e9e'' Didic) were engaged in farming. \n\nIn 1950, he graduated from the 7-grade school of his native village, after which he attended the middle school in [[Lipcani]], which he graduated in 1953.\n\n==Personal life==\nVieru was married to Raisa Vieru since 1959; they had two sons, Teodor and [[C\u0103lin Vieru]].\n\n==  Creative work ==\nHis first publishing debut was in 1957, a booklet of poems for children, ''\"Alarma\"'' (''\"Alarm\"''), appreciated by literary critics.The following year, Vieru graduated from the [[Ion Creang\u0103 Pedagogical State University]] in [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]] with a degree in history and philology. He was employed as an editor in the magazine called ''\"Sc\u00eenteia Leninist\u0103\"'' (''\"The Lenin\u2019s sparkle\"'') designed for children, currently it is called ''\"Noi\"'' (''\"We\"''), and the newspaper ''\"T\u00een\u0103rul leninist\"'' (''\"The Young Lenin\u2019s follower\"''), currently ''\"Florile Dalbe\"'' (''\"Glowing Flowers\"'').\n\nIn 1959, he became editor at the ''\"Nistru'\"' magazine, currently ''\"Basarabia\"'', a publication of the [[Writers' Union of Moldova]]. \n\nFrom 1960 to 1963, he served as editor in chief of the \"''Cartea Moldoveneasc\u0103''\" publishing house.\n\nIn 1967, Vieru's book \"Poetry for Readers of All Ages\" (published in 1965) was awarded the Moldavian Prize for Youth Literature. The following year, his book \"Your Name\" became part of the contemporary literature curriculum in Moldavian universities.\n\nHe wrote another children's story/picture book \"Bread and Dew\" which features Doru, a 4 or 5-year-old boy who lives in Chi\u0219in\u0103u with his parents.\n\nMany moldavian composers were inspired by the poetry of Grigore Vieru (songbook \"Poftim de intra\u021bi\", \"Cine crede\" etc.), the poet himself is the author of a lot of melodies (\"S\u0103 cre\u0219ti mare\" etc.) and since 1964 he began to collaborate with composer [[Yulia Tsibulskaya]] (\"Soare, soare\", \"Clopo\u021beii\", \"Stea-stea, logostea\", \"Ramule-neamule\", \"C\u00eent\u00eend cu iubire\" etc.).\n\nHe was a frequent guest of the \"Poetry House\" in [[Cociulia]] village, [[Cantemir District]]. The famous book for preschoolers ''\"Albinu\u021ba\"'' was also written here.\n\n1968 was turning point for the poet's destiny; this year became remarkable by the volume of lyrical ''\"Numele T\u0103u\"'' (\"Your name\"), with an introductory written by [[Ion Dru\u021b\u0103]]. The book was appreciated by literary critics as the most original poetic appearance. In the year of it publishing, it became a subject of the study at the university within the courses designated for the contemporary national literature. Three poems in the volume are entitled: ''[[Tudor Arghezi]]'', ''[[Lucian Blaga]]'', [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i|''Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i'']], and another two are dedicated to [[Nicolae Labi\u0219]] and [[Marin Sorescu]]. For the first time, in the post war period, such dedications has appeared in the Bessarabian lyrics.\n\n== Political activity ==\nSince 1971, Grigore Vieru has been a member of [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]].\n\nIn 1973, Grigore Vieru has passed the [[Prut]] within a delegation of Soviet writers. He participated in the meeting with the editors of the \"20th Century\" magazine: Dan Haulic\u0103, [[\u0218tefan Augustin Doina\u0219]], Ioanichie Olteanu, Geo \u0218erban, Tatiana Nicolescu. At his request, he has visited monasteries of [[Putna Monastery|Putna]], [[Vorone\u021b Monastery|Vorone\u021b]], [[Sucevi\u021ba Monastery|Sucevi\u021ba]], [[Dragomirna Monastery|Dragomirna]], [[V\u0103ratec Monastery|V\u0103ratec]]. He returned to Chi\u0219in\u0103u with a bag of books. Later the poet makes the following confession:{{cquote|''\"If somebody dreamed of getting to outer space, for my whole life I have dreamed of crossing the [[Prut River]]''\"}}\n\nIn 1974 and 1977, invited by the president of the [[Writers' Union of Romania|Romanian Writers' Union]], Vieru visited [[Bucharest]], [[Constan\u021ba]], [[Ia\u0219i]], and cities in [[Transylvania]].\n\nIn 1978, the \"[[Junimea]]\" publishing house printed \"The Friday Star\", Vieru's first work published in [[Romania]].\n\nIn 1989 he was elected member of [[Parliament of Moldova|Moldova's Parliament]] and campaigned for the [[Movement for unification of Romania and Moldova|unification of Romania and Moldova]]. The following year he was elected Honorary Member of the [[Romanian Academy]]. In 1992, the Romanian Academy recommended Vieru for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\nIn 1995, he became a member of the Board of the [[Romanian Radio Broadcasting Company]], and in 1996 he won several Romanian literary awards.\n\nIn 2000, Vieru was awarded the \"[[Mihai Eminescu|Eminescu]]\" Medal by the [[Government of Romania|Romanian government]].\n\n=== Involvement in the Bessarabia National Liberation Movement  ===\n[[File:Grigore Vieru, Ion Vatamanu si Serafim Saka.jpg|thumb|313x313px|right| Grigore Vieru, [[Ion Vatamanu]] and [[Serafim Saka]] in  '70.]]\nAt the end of the [[1980s|80s]], Grigore Vieru is in the first line of the National Liberation Movement in Bessarabia, his texts (including the songs laid on his lyrics) playing a big role in awakening of the national consciousness of Romanians in Bessarabia. Vieru is one of the founders of the People's Front of Moldova and is among the organizers and leaders of the Great National Assembly of August 27, 1989. He actively participates in the debates of the 13th session of the Supreme Soviet of the SSR, in which the [[Romanian language]] is voted as the official language and the transition to Latin spelling.\n\n==Death==\nOn January 16, 2009 Vieru suffered a serious traffic accident<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/Votes_Have_No_Language/1372065.html Death Of A Moldovan Poet]. rferl.org</ref> and was admitted to the Emergency Hospital in Chi\u0219in\u0103u. Grigore Vieru was in critical condition with polytrauma, closed cranio-cerebral trauma, cerebral contusion, and closed chest trauma, contusion of the heart and lungs and contusion of the abdominal organs, with minimal chances of survival.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2013-07-03\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/ESpVf| title=Imagini VIDEO cu ma\u015fina avariat\u0103 \u00een care se afla \u015fi Grigore Vieru. Po\u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 3, 2013| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> The road accident took place on the night of January 15 to 16, at 1:30 am on the R-3 route Chi\u0219in\u0103u \u2013 H\u00e2nce\u0219ti \u2013 Cimi\u0219lia \u2013 Basarabeasca.<ref name=\"Azi.md/ro/story/918_2020-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://www.azi.md/ro/story/918| title=Starea poetului Grigore Vieru ramane grava, medici de la Bucuresti sunt in drum spre Chisinau - Moldova Azi| newspaper=Azi.md/ro/story/918| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> At the driver\u2019s seat was Gheorghe Munteanu, emeritus artist of the Republic of Moldova and deputy director of the \"Joc\" folk dance troop of Chi\u0219in\u0103u, who being in an easier state.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2013-07-03\"/> At the time, he was out with friends celebrating the birthday of [[Mihai Eminescu]], a 19th-century Romanian poet. Vieru died on January 18, 2009, in the Emergency Hospital in Chi\u0219in\u0103u after two days after the accident, following a cardiac failure from which he could not be resuscitated.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-07-15\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/JLqD| title=(video) Grigore Vieru a murit. Eminescu l-a chemat la ceruri. Ziua \u00een\u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 15, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Mediafax_15:45\">{{Citation | url=https://www.mediafax.ro/cultura-media/poetul-grigore-vieru-a-decedat-video-3765578| title=Poetul Grigore Vieru a decedat (Video)| newspaper=Mediafax| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGrigore Vieru was buried on January 20, 2009 in Chi\u0219in\u0103u, at the Central Cemetery on Armeana street. The funeral were attended by tens of thousands of people, ''the divisions of Grigore Vieru'', as professor Dan Dungaciu called them in his article.<ref name=\"Limbaromana.md/index.php?go=articole&n=242_2020-04-21\">{{Citation | url=http://limbaromana.md/index.php?go=articole&n=242| title=Diviziile lui Grigore Vieru - LimbaRomana| newspaper=Limbaromana.md/index.php?go=articole&n=242| date= | accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Chi\u0219in\u0103u had not known such funerals since the burial of the spouses Doina and Ion Aldea Teodorovici. The day of January 20, 2009 was declared a day of mourning in the Republic of Moldova, at 10:00 the whole republic having a moment of silence. Vieru's funeral was also broadcast live by [[Teleradio Moldova]].\n\n== Posterity ==\n[[File:Bd. G. Vieru.JPG|The plaque on Grigore Vieru Boulevard in Chi\u0219in\u0103u|thumb|237x237px|left]]\n\nSeveral schools in the Republic of Moldova, a boulevard in Chi\u0219in\u0103u and a street in Ia\u0219i are called in honour of Grigore Vieru.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-08-01\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/gcew| title=Iasul are o strada Grigore Vieru | newspaper=archive.vn| date= August 1, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> On February 11, 2010, three days before his birthday, the poet's bust was installed in the [[Alley of Classics, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Alley of Classics]].<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-09-15\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/jw3o| title=Bustul lui Grigore Vieru va fi instalat la 12 februarie pe Aleea Clas\u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= September 15, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\nA street in [[Buz\u0103u]] is called in honour of Grigore Vieru: ''Grigore Vieru Street''.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012-07-24\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/Z2rN| title=Strada Grigore Vieru, \u00een Buz\u0103u| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 24, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1996 he won several Romanian literary awards, and in the same year on August 23rd, he won [[Order of the Republic (Moldova)]]. \n\nThe Romanian president [[Traian B\u0103sescu]] has posthumously awarded Grigore Vieru with the [[Order of the Star of Romania]], Grand Cross.<ref name=\"Flac\u0103ra TV_2015-01-19\">{{Citation | url=http://flacaratv.md/19-01-2009-poetului-grigore-vieru-i-a-fost-conferit-post-mortem-ordinul-national-steaua-romaniei.html| title=Poetului Grigore Vieru i-a fost conferit post-mortem Ordinul Na\u0163ional \u201eSteaua Rom\u00e2niei\u201d| newspaper=Flac\u0103ra TV| date= January 19, 2015| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Moments in Vieru's life ==\n[[File:Paul Mecet (12).jpg|Grigore Vieru, picture by Paul Mecet|300px|thumb]]\nIn the volume of lyrics  designed for children ''\"Trei iezi\"'' (''Three baby goats'') published in 1970, there was also the poem called ''\"Curcubeul\"'' (''The Rainbow''), in which Vieru, used the metaphor of the rainbow with three colours, praised the flag of all Romanians. In short period of time after the book publishing, the Soviet censorship withdrew the book from the bookstores, and the author was accused of diversion.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2012/08/01\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/tO51| title=Poetul Basarabean Grigore Vieru| newspaper=archive.vn| date= August 1, 2012| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Also in 1970, has appeared ''The Abecedarul'' book developed by Vieru in collaboration with the writer Spiridon Vangheli. Even nowadays, this textbook, which was edited many times over time, still teaches the the first class little Bessarabians. In 1989, Vieru and Vangheli also made the Latin alphabet version of ''The Abecedarul''.\n\nVieru wrote, among many others, the lyrics for the soundtrack of the cartoon film ''[[Maria, Mirabela]]'', and the Vieru\u2019s poem ''\"Drag\u0103 Otee\"'' (''Dear Otee'') has been sung by Iurie Sadovnic. Later, the song was taken over by [[Zdob \u0219i Zdub]].\n\nIn 1988, in the newspaper ''[[Literatura \u015fi Arta]]'' (''Literature and Art'') in Chi\u0219in\u0103u, the first Latin-written text from post-war Bessarabia has appeared. The author was Grigore Vieru.<ref name=\"archive.vn_2013-07-06\">{{Citation | url=http://archive.today/zlHKB| title=EDITORIAL: Poetul Grigore Vieru s-a preschimbat in iarba (Realitatea \u2026| newspaper=archive.vn| date= July 6, 2013| accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1989, Vieru has got the approval of the Soviet authorities to publish the weekly ''Literatura si Arta'' in Latin writing, the editors of the newspaper mentioned that in all Soviet Moldova there were no typewriter of Latin letters, except the one from the Academy of Sciences of the [[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic|MSSR]] and of professor Iulius Popa from [[B\u0103l\u021bi]]. Under these conditions, Grigore Vieru and the editor-in-chief of ''Literatura \u0219i Arta'', [[Nicolae Dabija]], went to [[Bucharest]] to get the typewriter for the newspaper. The Romanian authorities were delaying the answer, and the antiquarian shop from which they could buy such a device was closed these days because of some technical issues. However, Vieru and Dabija were helped by the priest Vasile \u021aepordei, who brought to the station a bag containing the 31 metallic signs of the Latin alphabet, cut by him from his own typewriter. In Chi\u0219in\u0103u, the Latin signs are welded to a typewriter instead of the Cyrillic ones, so ''Literatura \u0219i Arta'' magazine became the first newspaper of Bessarabia to start systematically coming out in Latin spelling.\n\nIn 1994 the neo-communists of the [[Democratic Agrarian Party]], who came to power in Moldova, have gave up to the state hymn ''[[De\u0219teapt\u0103-te, rom\u00e2ne!]]'' (''Awake the romanian'') and have proposed to the poet Grigore Vieru and the composer [[Eugen Doga]] to compose the lyrics and the music for a new hymn. They both refuse. Grigore Vieru has wrote in the ''Literatura \u0219i Arta'' magazine the following: {{cquote|''\"Historical justice will blame the poets and composers who will dare to raise their hands on the National Hymn \"Desteapt\u0103-te Rom\u00e2ne!\" stooping instead of his historical need and brilliance.\"''}}<ref name=\"adev2014-06-09\">{{Citation | url=https://adevarul.ro/moldova/actualitate/20-ani-desteapta-te-romane-1_53955a820d133766a86b3947/index.html| title=20 de ani f\u0103r\u0103 \u201eDe\u015fteapt\u0103-te, rom\u00e2ne!\u201c| newspaper=Adev\u0103rul| date= June 9, 2014| accessdate=April 21, 2020 |author = Https://facebook. Com/100003970736071}}</ref>\n\n== Operas ==\n* 1957 \u2013  ''\"Alarma\"'' (''Alarm'') (lyrics for children);\n* 1958 \u2013 ''\"Muzicu\u021be\"'' (''Musical notes'') (lyrics for children);\n* 1961 \u2013 ''\"F\u0103t-Frumos curcubeul \u0219i Bun\u0103 ziua, fulgilor!\"'' (''F\u0103t-Frumos the rainbow and Good morning, the flakes!'') by the \"Cartea Moldoveneasc\u0103\" publishing house;\n* 1963 \u2013 ''\"Mul\u021bumim pentru pace\"'' (''Thanks for peace'') (lyrics)  and ''\"F\u0103gura\u0219i\"'' (lyrics, stories and songs);\n* 1964 - The magazine ''\"Nistru\"'' published the poem ''\"Leg\u0103m\u00e2nt\"'' (''The Covenan''), dedicated to poet Mihai Eminescu;\n* 1965 \u2013 ''\"Versuri pentru cititorii de toate v\u00e2rstele\"'' (''The lyrics for readers of all ages''), with an introductory word written by Ion Dru\u021b\u0103 and for this lyrics the poet was awarded ''The Comsomol Republican Prize'' in the field of children's and youth literature (1967);\n* 1967 \u2013 ''\"Poezii de seama voastr\u0103\"'' (''Poems of your age'') (\"Lumina\" publishing house);\n* 1968 \u2013 ''\"B\u0103rba\u021bii Moldovei\"'' (''Moldova\u2019s Men''), designed to the \"nationalist\" Nicolae Testimi\u021beanu (\"Nistru\" magazine). The whole circulation was stopped, and the dedication taken away;\n* 1969 \u2013 ''\"Duminica cuvintelor\"'' (''The  Words of Sunday'') by \"Lumina\" publishing house with illustrations by Igor Vieru, a book much loved by pre-schoolers, which is present in every kindergarten;\n* 1970 - ''\"Abecedarul\"'' (\"Lumina\" publishing house) - in collaboration with Spiridon Vangheli and painter [[Igor Vieru]];\n* 1972 \u2013 ''\"Trei iezi\"'' (''Three baby goats'');\n* 1974 \u2013 ''\"Aproape\"'' (''Nearby'') (lyrics, with color illustrations by Isai C\u00e2rmu);\n* 1975 \u2013 ''\"Mama\"'' (''The Mother'') (\"Lumina\" publishing house - book for the little ones, illustrated by Igor Vieru);\n* 1976 \u2013 ''\"Un verde ne vede!\"''(''A green one sees us!'') (\"Lumina\" publishing house \u2013 for this volume of lyrics the poem is awarded the State Prize of the Republic of Moldova (1978);\n* 1989 \u2013 ''\"Metafore Albastre\"'' - ''\u0421\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0444\u043e\u0440\u0438'' (''The Blue metaphors'') - (\"Narodna cultura\" publishing house, [[Sofia]] - in the collection Globus poetic, translation into [[bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] by Ognean Stamboliev;\n* 2010 \u2013 ''\"Mi-e dor de piatr\u0103\"'' - ''\u0416\u0430\u043b \u043c\u0438 \u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u043c\u044a\u043a\u0430'' (''I miss the stone'') \u2013 publishing house Avangardprint, Bulgaria - translation into Bulgarian and preface by Ognean Stamboliev - 100 poems.\nIt is present in:\n* Streiflicht \u2013 Eine Auswahl zeitgen\u00f6ssischer rum\u00e4nischer Lyrik (81 rum\u00e4nische Autoren), - \"Lumina piezi\u0219\u0103\" (''Pie light'') the bilingual anthology consisted of 81 Romanian writers, translated by Christian W. Schenk, Dionysos Verlag 1994, ISBN 3980387119\n\n== The music on Vieru\u2019s lyrics ==\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/sarmaticus/d21ef57bbbd618 Maria Mirabela]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/martti/06fece8482cab1 Drag\u0103 Otee]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/septimosaur/d7a64a98dab371 Pentru Ea]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cBLl2zkyQlw R\u0103sai]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qD3LYd6ScNI Eminescu]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ve_wqvvoS30 La m\u0103n\u0103stirea C\u0103priana (Clopotul \u00cenvierii)]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uWZ4h5zCJ6o L\u0103sa\u021bi-ne \u00een legea noastr\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XdHQZo6Bdjs Dou\u0103 lacrimi gemene (Chi\u0219in\u0103u \u0219i Bucure\u0219ti)]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xb9dZr3DkrU O serenad\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HKkPPwkTQks Melancolie]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/pld/f278d31bd7bccb Ultima or\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RHzzs7KY-0Y Reaprinde\u021bi candela]\n* [http://www.trilulilu.ro/Glory/ff1920945d5252 Mi-e dor de tine, mam\u0103]\n* [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gxZxkmWT-1M  Codrul e frumos cu floare]\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery perrow=\"\">\nFile:Grigore Vieru monument in Soroca park.jpg|Grigore Vieru in [[Soroca]]\nFile:Grigore Vieru din B\u0103l\u021bi.jpg|[[Alley of Classics, B\u0103l\u021bi]] \nFile:Galati biblioteca din Eurogara CFR Calatori.jpg|Eurostation of [[Gala\u021bi]] Grigore Vieru library \n</gallery>\n\n== Presence in English language anthologies ==\n\n* ''Testament \u2013 Anthology of Modern Romanian Verse / Testament - Antologie de Poezie Rom\u00e2n\u0103 Modern\u0103 \u2013 Bilingual Edition English & Romanian'' \u2013 [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and translator) with Eva Foster and Daniel Reynaud \u2013 [[Editura Minerva|Minerva]] Publishing 2012 and 2015 (second edition) - {{ISBN|978-973-21-1006-5}}\n* ''Testament - Anthology of Romanian Verse - American Edition -'' monolingual English language edition - [[Daniel Ionita]] (editor and principal translator) with Eva Foster, Daniel Reynaud and Rochelle Bews - Australian-Romanian Academy for Culture - 2017 - {{ISBN|978-0-9953502-0-5}}\n* ''The Bessarabia of My Soul / Basarabia Sufletului Meu -'' a collection of poetry from the Republic of Moldova - bilingual English/Romanian - [[Daniel Ionita]] and Maria Tonu (editors), with Eva Foster, Daniel Reynaud and Rochelle Bews - MediaTon, Toronto, Canada - 2018 - {{ISBN|978-1-7751837-9-2}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Unification of Romania and Moldova]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Grigore Vieru}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://archive.today/OJ2CK Grigore Vieru \u2013 virtual monument]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070124013536/http://biserica.org/Churches/SfantaTreime/Bios/GrigoreVieru.html A biography of Grigore Vieru]\n* {{in lang|ro}} {{YouTube|gxZxkmWT-1M|The forest is beautiful with a flower (Iu.\u0162ibulschi \u2013 Gr.Vieru)}}\n* {{in lang|ro}} {{YouTube|KehpQBEiN0g|Christ is not to blame (Iu. \u0162ibulschi \u2013 Gr. Vieru)}}\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.poezie.ro/index.php/essay/1819124/Pe_cer_a_mai_urcat_o_stea Valerian Ciobanu-Vieru: Pe cer a mai urcat o stea], poezie.ro\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.formula-as.ro/2009/853/planete-culturale-30/la-moartea-lui-grigore-vieru-10684 La moartea lui Grigore Vieru]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.formula-as.ro/2011/958/planete-culturale-30/grigore-vieru-evocare-de-nicolae-dabija-13446 GRIGORE VIERU - Evocare de NICOLAE DABIJA]\n\n{{Anti-communism in Bessarabia and Northern Bukovina}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vieru, Grigore}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Briceni District]]\n[[Category:Moldovan poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian poets]]\n[[Category:Romanian male poets]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Star of Romania]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Corresponding members of the Romanian Academy]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Republic (Moldova)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grigore_Vieru"}
{"title_page": "Adoor (State Assembly constituency)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Kerala Niyamasabha Constituency\n| constituency number    = 115\n| name                   = Adoor <br/> \u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c\n| existence              = 1965 - present\n| reserved               = [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|SC]]\n| current mla            = [[Chittayam Gopakumar]]\n| party                  = [[Communist Party of India]] \n| front                  = {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| electedbyyear          = [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election|2016]]\n| district               = [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]]\n| electorate             =   2,08,432 (2016)\n| self governed segments =\n}}\n\n'''Adoor State assembly constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d2e\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 140 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies at the state [[Kerala]] in southern [[India]]. It is also one of the 7 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies included in the [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)|Pathanamthitta Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = https://pathanamthitta.nic.in/ml/elected-members-and-constituencies\n |website     = pathanamthitta.nic.in\n |title       = State Assembly Constituencies in Pathanamthitta district\n |accessdate  = 16 March 2020\n}}</ref> The candidacy for MLA of the constituency is restricted to members of [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Castes]] only. The current MLA is [[Chittayam Gopakumar]] of [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]]\n==See also==\n* [[Adoor]]\n* [[Pathanamthitta district]]\n* [[List of constituencies of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n* [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kerala Assembly Constituencies}}\n\n{{Kerala Niyamasabha elections}}\n\n[[Category:State assembly constituencies in Pathanamthitta district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Kerala Niyamasabha Constituency\n| constituency number    = 115\n| name                   = Adoor <br/> \u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c\n| existence              = 1965 - present\n| reserved               = [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|SC]]\n| current mla            = [[Chittayam Gopakumar]]\n| party                  = [[Communist Party of India]] \n| front                  = {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| electedbyyear          = [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election|2016]]\n| district               = [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]]\n| electorate             =   2,08,432 (2016)\n| self governed segments =\n}}\n\n'''Adoor State assembly constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d05\u0d1f\u0d42\u0d7c \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d2e\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 140 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies at the state [[Kerala]] in southern [[India]]. It is also one of the 7 [[Kerala Legislative Assembly|state legislative assembly]] constituencies included in the [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)|Pathanamthitta Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = https://pathanamthitta.nic.in/ml/elected-members-and-constituencies\n |website     = pathanamthitta.nic.in\n |title       = State Assembly Constituencies in Pathanamthitta district\n |accessdate  = 16 March 2020\n}}</ref> The current MLA is [[Chittayam Gopakumar]] of [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]]\n==See also==\n* [[Adoor]]\n* [[Pathanamthitta district]]\n* [[List of constituencies of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n* [[2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kerala Assembly Constituencies}}\n\n{{Kerala Niyamasabha elections}}\n\n[[Category:State assembly constituencies in Pathanamthitta district]]\n", "name_user": "Aswin8", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adoor_(State_Assembly_constituency)"}
{"title_page": "Doubles (2000 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Doubles\n| image = \n| director = [[Pandiarajan]]\n| writer = Pandiarajan\n| starring = [[Prabhu Deva]]<br/>[[Meena Durairaj|Meena]]<br>[[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]]\n| producer = K. Rajan\n| music = [[Srikanth Deva]]\n| cinematography = [[R. Raghunatha Reddy]]\n| editing = [[B. Lenin]],<br>[[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| distributor =\n| released = 11 August 2000\n| runtime = \n| language = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n}}\n\n'''''Doubles''''' is a 2000 [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Pandiarajan]], who also played a guest appearance in the film. Produced by K. Rajan, the film stars [[Prabhu Deva]], [[Meena Durairaj|Meena]], and [[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]] in the lead roles, while [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]], [[Manivannan]], and [[Kovai Sarala]] play supporting roles. The film's score and soundtrack are composed by debutant [[Srikanth Deva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com/movies/kollywood/Doubles/4540 |title=Find tamil movie Doubles |work=Jointscene |accessdate=2009-12-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100201140607/http://www.jointscene.com/movies/Kollywood/Doubles/4540 |archivedate=1 February 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>http://www.thiraipadam.com/cgi-bin/movie_review.pl?id=107&user_name=bbalaji&review_lang=english&lang=english</ref> The film released on 11 August 2000.\n\n==Plot==\nThe movie starts projecting Prabhu ([[Prabhu Deva]]) as a shopkeeper who sells toys to kids. He does all possible crazy actions in the world, which really irritates everyone. He has many bad habits, such as drinking and smoking. Prabhu marries Meena ([[Meena Durairaj|Meena]]), but she wants her husband to be like Sree Ram. Prabhu acts as if he is a nice guy and also gets caught a few times when he tries to overact. Rasika ([[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]]), Meena's close friend, comes and stays with Meena as she is doing her final year in Madras Medical College. Prabhu had earlier pinched Rasika's hip when she was travelling in a bus. He gets slapped by Rasika and was thrown from that bus before she meets him. Rasika takes the task of seducing Prabhu to prove that he is a womaniser to Meena and fails in many attempts. The movie ends as Meena dies of jaundice and Prabhu realising that his true love was only for Meena. Rasika marries Ganesh ([[Pandiarajan]]), who comes for one scene in the ending.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Prabhu Deva]] as Prabhu\n*[[Meena Durairaj|Meena]] as Meena\n*[[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]] as Rasika\n*[[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]]\n*[[Manivannan]]\n*[[Kovai Sarala]]\n*[[Pandiarajan]] as Ganesh (cameo)\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack was composed by [[Srikanth Deva]], son of music composer [[Deva (composer)|Deva]], who made his debut as composer with this film. \"Adi Kadhal Oru Kannil\" was a chartbuster. All lyrics were written by [[Vairamuthu]].<ref>https://www.saavn.com/s/album/tamil/Doubles-2000/2YCdWqlXR-w_</ref>\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Doubles\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Srikanth Deva]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   =  Jan 1, 2000\n| recorded   = 2000\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 28:02\n| label      = Five Star Audio\n| producer   = [[Srikanth Deva]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = [[Kuththu]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline       = Track list\n| extra_column   = Singer(s)\n| total_length   = 28:02\n| title1          = Colourful Nilavu\n| extra1          = [[Vasundhara Das]], Timmy\n| length1         = 5:02\n| title2          = Hey Pondattikkum I \n| extra2          = [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Sujatha Mohan]]\n| length2         = 4:01\n| title3  =  Hey Pondattikkum II\n| extra3  = [[Devan Ekambaram]], Sujatha Mohan\n| length3 = 4:01\n| title4  = Adi Kadhal\n| extra4  = [[P. Unnikrishnan]], [[Harini (singer)|Harini]]\n| length4 = 5:17\n| title5  = Rama Rama\n| extra5  = [[Swarnalatha]], [[Anuradha Sriram]]\n| length5 = 5:14\n| title6  = Naan Ippo\n| extra6  = [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]]\n| length6 = 4:27\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Pandiarajan}}\n\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Srikanth Deva]]\n\n{{2000s-Tamil-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Doubles\n| image = \n| director = [[Pandiarajan]]\n| writer = Pandiarajan\n| starring = [[Prabhu Deva]]<br/>[[Meena Durairaj|Meena]]<br>[[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]]\n| producer = K. Rajan\n| music = [[Srikanth Deva]]\n| cinematography = [[R. Raghunatha Reddy]]\n| editing = [[B. Lenin]],<br>[[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| distributor =\n| released = 11 August 2000\n| runtime = \n| language = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n}}\n\n'''''Doubles''''' is a 2000 [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Pandiarajan]], who also played a guest appearance in the film. Produced by K. Rajan, the film stars [[Prabhu Deva]], [[Meena Durairaj|Meena]], and [[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]] in the lead roles, while [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]], [[Manivannan]], and [[Kovai Sarala]] play supporting roles. The film's score and soundtrack are composed by debutant [[Srikanth Deva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com/movies/kollywood/Doubles/4540 |title=Find tamil movie Doubles |work=Jointscene |accessdate=2009-12-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100201140607/http://www.jointscene.com/movies/Kollywood/Doubles/4540 |archivedate=1 February 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>http://www.thiraipadam.com/cgi-bin/movie_review.pl?id=107&user_name=bbalaji&review_lang=english&lang=english</ref> The film released on 11 August 2000.\n\n==Plot==\nThe movie starts projecting Prabhu ([[Prabhu Deva]]) as a shopkeeper who sells toys to kids. He does all possible crazy actions in the world, which really irritates everyone. He has many bad habits, such as drinking and smoking. Prabhu gets married to Meena ([[Meena Durairaj|Meena]]), but she wants her husband to be like Sree Ram. Prabhu acts as if he is a nice guy and also gets caught a few times when he tries to overact. Rasika ([[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]]), Meena's close friend, comes and stays with Meena as she is doing her final year in Madras Medical College. Prabhu had earlier pinched Rasika's hip when she was travelling in a bus. He gets slapped by Rasika and was thrown from that bus before she meets him. Rasika takes the task of seducing Prabhu to prove that he is a womaniser to Meena and fails in many attempts. The movie ends as Meena dies of jaundice and Prabhu realising that his true love was only for Meena. Rasika marries Ganesh ([[Pandiarajan]]), who comes for one scene in the ending.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Prabhu Deva]] as Prabhu\n*[[Meena Durairaj|Meena]] as Meena\n*[[Sangeetha Krish|Sangeetha]] as Rasika\n*[[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]]\n*[[Manivannan]]\n*[[Kovai Sarala]]\n*[[Pandiarajan]] as Ganesh (cameo)\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack was composed by [[Srikanth Deva]], son of music composer [[Deva (composer)|Deva]], who made his debut as composer with this film. \"Adi Kadhal Oru Kannil\" was a chartbuster. All lyrics were written by [[Vairamuthu]].<ref>https://www.saavn.com/s/album/tamil/Doubles-2000/2YCdWqlXR-w_</ref>\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Doubles\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Srikanth Deva]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   =  Jan 1, 2000\n| recorded   = 2000\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 28:02\n| label      = Five Star Audio\n| producer   = [[Srikanth Deva]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = [[Kuththu]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline       = Track list\n| extra_column   = Singer(s)\n|